# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gloucester
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gloucester/1896-gloucester-smallpox-epidemic] The **1896 Gloucester smallpox epidemic** affected more than 2,000 people in Gloucester between five January and 27 July 1896.
[src:gloucester/1896-gloucester-smallpox-epidemic] A large number of the town's population were not vaccinated.
[src:gloucester/1896-gloucester-smallpox-epidemic] On 13 August 1896, the Royal Commission on Vaccination's report on the epidemic was published by the Royal College of Surgeons of England.
[src:gloucester/1896-gloucester-smallpox-epidemic] In Britain, smallpox vaccination became compulsory in the 1850s.
[src:gloucester/1896-gloucester-smallpox-epidemic] In Gloucester, a smallpox outbreak occurred in the mid-1870s.
[src:gloucester/1896-gloucester-smallpox-epidemic] However, the 1890s also saw anti-vaccination beliefs.
[src:gloucester/1896-gloucester-smallpox-epidemic] President of the Local Government Board Thomas Russell stated in 1896 that, between 4 January and 25 July 1896, the number of cases of smallpox in Gloucester totalled 2,008.
[src:gloucester/1896-gloucester-smallpox-epidemic] Ethel Cromwell was around 14 years old when her photograph was taken in a hospital in Gloucester, following admission with smallpox.
[src:gloucester/1896-gloucester-smallpox-epidemic] An isolation hospital, the Stroud Road hospital was built in response.
[src:gloucester/1896-gloucester-smallpox-epidemic] One reaction was that it led to prejudice against Gloucesterians.
[src:gloucester/1896-gloucester-smallpox-epidemic] On 13 August 1896, the Royal College of Surgeons of England published a report by the Royal Commission on Vaccination, whose members included Lord Herschell and Sir James Paget.
[src:gloucester/1896-gloucester-smallpox-epidemic] A subsequent outbreak of smallpox occurred in 1923.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] The **1991 Rugby World Cup** (French: *Coupe du monde de rugby 1991*) was the second edition of the Rugby World Cup, and was jointly hosted by England, Scotland, Wales, Ireland and France: at the time, the five European countries who participated in the Five Nations Championship.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] This was the first Rugby World Cup to be staged in the northern hemisphere, with England the hosts of the final.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] Also for the first time, qualifying competitions were introduced as the number of entrants had increased, from 16 nations four years earlier, to 33 countries.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] The eight quarter-finalists from 1987 qualified automatically with the remaining eight spots contested through qualifiers by 25 countries.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] This resulted in only one new side qualifying for the tournament, Western Samoa replacing Tonga.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] The same 16-team pool/knock-out format was used with just minor changes to the points system.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] South Africa was again not included because of sanctions imposed on the country by the International Rugby Board (IRB), due to the government's apartheid policies.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] The pool stages produced a major upset when Western Samoa, who were making their debut in the tournament, defeated the 1987 semi-finalists Wales 16–13 in Cardiff.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] Along with the other results in the group, this led to the elimination of Wales, who finished third in Pool 3.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] Also notable in pool play was that Canada finished second in their pool to qualify for the quarter-finals, which remains their best performance in the World Cup.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] Fiji, as quarter-finalists four years earlier, had expected to occupy that position, but after the upset loss to Canada and a hammering by France, they lost even their final match against the unfancied Romanian team.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] Earlier, the opening match had pitted the holders New Zealand against the hosts England: New Zealand overturned a narrow half-time deficit to win the match and the pool, both teams qualifying for the quarter-finals with easy victories in their other matches.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] Scotland beat Ireland to top their pool, again both teams qualifying.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] In the quarter-finals, neither Canada nor Western Samoa proved a match for New Zealand or Scotland, respectively.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] Meanwhile, England knocked out 1987 finalist France in a bruising encounter.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] Australia pipped Ireland 19–18 in a thrilling match at Lansdowne Road, with a last-gasp try from fly-half Michael Lynagh coming after the Irish took an unexpected 18–15 lead.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] The semi-finals produced two tight matches: England overcame Scotland 9–6, a late drop goal deciding a tryless match in a torrential downpour at Murrayfield Stadium, and Australia defeated the defending champions New Zealand 16–6 at Lansdowne Road.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] The final was played at Twickenham Stadium in London, and saw Australia win 12–6 against England, with a first-half try from prop Tony Daly.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] The following 16 teams, shown by region, qualified for the 1991 Rugby World Cup.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] Of the 16 teams, eight of those places were automatically filled by quarter-finalists from the 1987 World Cup and did not have to play any qualification matches.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] 25 nations competed in a qualification process designed to fill the remaining eight spots, bringing the total participation to 33 nations.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] In the event, there was only one change from the 1987 tournament, with Western Samoa appearing in place of Tonga.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] As in the 1987 Rugby World Cup the 16 nations were divided into four pools of four nations, with each nation playing their other pool opponents once, every nation playing three times during the pool stages.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] Nations were awarded 2 points for a win, 1 for a draw and zero for a loss, the top two nations of every pool advanced to the quarter-finals.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] The runners-up of each pool faced the winners of a different pool in the quarter-finals.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] The winners moved on to the semi-finals, with the winners then moving onto the final, and the losers of the semi-finals contesting a third/fourth place play off.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] A total of 32 matches (24 in the pool stage and eight in the knock-out stage) were played throughout the tournament over 30 days from 3 October 1991 to 2 November 1991.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] The tournament's top point scorer was Ireland's Ralph Keyes, who scored 68 points.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] David Campese and Jean-Baptiste Lafond scored the most tries, six in total.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] The event was broadcast in the United Kingdom by ITV who took over the rights from the BBC.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] 13 million people in the United Kingdom watched the final.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] In Australia it was the second and the last (as of the 2023 tournament) Rugby World Cup to be broadcast on ABC television as, from 1995, the commercial networks 7, 9 and 10 would all take over the broadcast rights sometimes in partnership with pay and streaming broadcasters Fox and Stan.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] In New Zealand, it was broadcast by TVNZ.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] In France, it was broadcast by TF1 instead of France's traditional Rugby broadcasters Antenne2.
[src:gloucester/1991-rugby-world-cup] ITV, TF1 and RTE were the host broadcasters broadcasting the pictures around the world as well to their own countries.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A series of large floods occurred in parts of the United Kingdom during the summer of 2007.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] June was one of the wettest months on record in the United Kingdom (see List of weather records).
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Average rainfall across the country was 5.5 inches (140 mm); more than double the June average.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Some areas received a month's worth of precipitation in 24 hours.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] It was the UK's wettest May–July period since records began in 1776.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] July had unusually unsettled weather and above-average rainfall through the month, peaking on 20 July as an active frontal system dumped more than 4.7 inches (120 mm) of rain in southern England.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Civil and military authorities described the June and July rescue efforts as the biggest in the UK in peacetime.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Environment Agency described the July floods as critical and expected them to exceed the 1947 benchmark.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] June 2007 started quietly with an anticyclone to the north of the United Kingdom maintaining a dry, cool easterly flow.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] From 10 June the high pressure began to break down as an upper trough moved into the area, triggering thunderstorms that caused flooding in Northern Ireland on 12 June.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Later that week, a slow-moving area of low pressure from the west of Biscay moved east across the British Isles.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] At the same time an associated occluded front moved into northern England, becoming very active as it did so, with the peak rainfall on 15 June.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Rainfall records were broken across the region, leading to localised flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] As it weakened, the front moved north into Scotland on 16 June and left England and Wales with a very unstable airmass, frequent heavy showers, thunderstorms and cloudy conditions.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] This led to localised flash flooding and prevented significant drying where earlier rains had fallen.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 25 June, another unseasonably low pressure (993 hPa / 29.3 inHg) depression, Cyclone Uriah, moved across England.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The associated front settled over northern and eastern England and dumped more than 3.9 inches (100 mm) of rain in places.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The combination of high rainfall and high water levels from the earlier rainfall led to extensive flooding across many parts of England and Wales, with the Midlands, Gloucestershire, Worcestershire, South, West and East Yorkshire the most affected.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Gales along the east coast also caused storm damage.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] RAF Fylingdales on the North York Moors reported rainfall totals of 4.1 inches (103 mm) in 24 hours, an estimated 3.9 inches (100 mm) in Hull and 3.0 inches (77 mm) on Emley Moor in West Yorkshire.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Until 2007, the average monthly total for June for the whole UK was 2.86 inches (72.6 mm).
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 27 June, the Met Office released an early warning of severe weather for the approaching weekend, stating that 0.79 to 1.97 inches (20 to 50 mm) of rain could fall in some areas, raising the possibility of more flooding within the already saturated flood plains.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 20 July, another active frontal system moved across southern England.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Many places recorded a month's rainfall or more in one day.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Met Office at RAF Brize Norton in Oxfordshire reported 4.98 inches (126.6 mm): a sixth of its annual rainfall.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The college at Pershore in Worcestershire reported 5.60 inches (142.2 mm), causing the Environment Agency to issue 16 further severe flood warnings.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 21 July, many towns and villages were flooded, with Gloucestershire, Worcestershire, Warwickshire, Wiltshire, Oxfordshire, Berkshire, London and South Wales facing the brunt of the heavy rainfall.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Climate researchers suggested that the unusual weather leading to the floods might be linked to that year's appearance of La Nina in the Pacific Ocean, and to the jet stream being further south than normal.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] England was affected by the June and July floods, with the North badly hit in June, the West badly hit in July, and many areas hit in both.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] It was England's wettest July on record.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Gloucestershire was the worst affected county – with both some minor flooding in June, and major flooding in July.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Non-administrative counties and administrative counties affected by the flooding are given below.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 25 July, a number of low-lying parts adjacent to the river in Bedford and Luton were flooded and one man drowned attempting to swim across the River Great Ouse in Bedford.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Parts of Felmersham and Turvey were also flooded.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 20 July, the M4 was closed after a landslide caused by flooding between Junctions 12 and 13 eastbound.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Approximately 1,100 properties in Thatcham were affected by flash flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 21 July, Newbury and Maidenhead town centres were flooded, the shopping mall in Maidenhead was closed and parts of the Glade Festival were flooded.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Officials warned that the River Thames, the River Ock, and its tributaries from Charney could burst their banks.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In Reading, rail services to the southwest were affected, and westbound trains from Paddington could go no further.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The flood waters affected the Atomic Weapons Establishment at Burghfield, which handles the United Kingdom's nuclear warheads, resulting in a suspension of work for almost a year.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 3 June, Stoke Goldington suffered flash flooding affecting 25 homes.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Stoke Goldington was affected again on 3 July, with 10 houses being flooded.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 24 July, four bridges in St Neots were shut when the river level peaked, and the Environment Agency warned residents in the St Neots, Paxton and Offords areas to expect flooding that night.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 25 July, parts of St Ives were flooded.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Later the same day, the Environment Agency advised residents near the River Great Ouse that the peak had passed and further flooding was unlikely.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 June, heavy rainfall caused the postponement of the fourth test match between England and the West Indies at the Riverside Ground, Chester-le-Street.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 23 June, flash floods affected parts of Darlington and Stanhope Road, Northgate, St Cuthbert's Way, Parkgate and Haughton Road were closed after water levels rose by about 2 feet (0.6 m).
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] It has also led to Woodland Road to improve its drainage to prevent such flooding on one of the main roads out the town.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 17 July, flooding affected Peterlee town centre, closing shops and a local school.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A 64-year-old man hit his head and died after trying to bail out his flooded home in Alston, Cumbria.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 25 June, flooding affected properties in Coal Aston, Calow and Chesterfield town centre, and the A617 was covered by more than 2 feet (0.6 m) of floodwater causing traffic delays.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 19 July, Gloucestershire Fire and Rescue Service attended 1,800 calls in a 48-hour period, compared with the usual 8,000 calls a year.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 22 July, Gloucester City A.F.C.'s Stadium was flooded, and the Tewkesbury road at Longford was completely impassable by the Longford Inn.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Tewkesbury was completely cut off with no road access, parts of the town were under around 3 feet (0.9 m) of water and flood waters entered Tewkesbury Abbey for the first time in 247 years.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Tewkesbury's Mythe Water Treatment Works were flooded.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Severn Trent Water warned that treated water would run out by early Sunday evening in Tewkesbury, Cheltenham, Gloucester and surrounding areas.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Combined military and civil emergency services tried to prevent floods reaching the Walham electricity substation in Gloucester supplying half a million people.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 23 July, 50,000 Gloucestershire homes were left without electricity after a major electricity substation in Castle Meads had to be turned off.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Efforts to stop flooding at Walham substation succeeded; the Castle Meads substation was repaired the next day.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 24 July, an estimated 420,000 people were without running water, including most of the population of Gloucester, Cheltenham, and Tewkesbury.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Emergency services continued repair work at the Mythe water-treatment works, but Severn Trent Water estimated that water supplies would not be restored for at least 14 days.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] 900 drinking water bowsers were brought in, and the Army was mobilised to distribute three million bottles of water a day and keep the bowsers filled.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Coors, Carlsberg, Scottish and Newcastle, Inbev and Greene King brewing companies offered 23 beer tankers to help supply drinking water.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 26 July, Severn Trent Water organised a temporary non-potable water supply to 10,000 homes in Tewkesbury.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] It was not until 7 August – 16 days after Mythe Treatment Works stopped pumping – that the tap water for the 140,000 homes affected was again declared safe to drink.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A man and his 24-year-old son died from asphyxiation from carbon monoxide poisoning on 27 July when attempting to stop flooding in the unventilated Tewkesbury Rugby Football Club cellar.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 28 July, the body of a 19-year-old man, reported missing seven days earlier, was recovered in Tewkesbury.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 20 July, flooding occurred in many parts of Greater London.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Water and power supplies were not disrupted but parts of South West London were under 2 feet (61 cm) of water.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Two of four rail lines in South Croydon were closed by landslips.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The London Underground was severely disrupted and 25 stations were closed.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 19 June, Herefordshire was affected by flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The M50 motorway near Ledbury was closed on 22 July due to flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] More than 5,200 people in and around Bromyard were without clean water on 22 and 23 July after the pumps at the Whitbourne works failed.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Once supply was restored residents were urged by Welsh Water to boil their tap-water until further notice.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The village of Hampton Bishop, 3 miles (5 km) from the city of Hereford, was surrounded and flooded by water after the River Lugg burst its banks.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On the afternoon of 24 July the Fire Service began pumping flood water out of the village, but not before 130 residents were evacuated.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Some houses, including the Herefordshire home of *Daily Mail* writer Quentin Letts, were flooded by a torrent of water gushing from what had previously been only a small, unnamed brook north of Ross-on-Wye.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Residents of East Bromyard were rescued after the River Frome burst its banks.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 June, Lostock Hall and Penwortham near Preston were hit by flash floods.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 3 July, heavy rain caused flooding in Earby and Ribchester, affecting homes and causing the Royal Lancashire Show to be cancelled on 9 July.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 4 July, the Blackburn Mela was cancelled due to ground conditions.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 18 July, Walton-le-Dale near Preston was hit by flash floods.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Louth and Horncastle were severely flooded, some roads in that area becoming impassable.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Children at a school in Horncastle were evacuated because of floods.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] More than 600-flood related calls occurred across the county.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In Lincoln, mainly round the Stamp End area, a house called Shuttleworth House was completely flooded with water in its insides.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] After power was lost in the area, more than 200 people were rescued in dinghies.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 27 June 2007, flash flooding caused extensive damage to the villages of Lambley, Woodborough and Burton Joyce.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Major towns were hit including Mansfield and Hucknall but not as severely as Lambley.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The same day, flooding occurred at Retford and Worksop after the River Idle and River Ryton respectively overtopped their banks.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Many rivers burst their banks, including both the Thames and the Cherwell in Oxford and the Ock in Abingdon the Windrush in Witney and the Evenlode.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 21 July, Banbury and Witney were flooded.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Oxford, particularly Botley, was flooded and some 300 people were evacuated.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 22 July, the Environment Agency warned of further flooding and 1,500 people in Abingdon were evacuated.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Forty thousand sandbags were transported from Grantham in Lincolnshire to Abingdon and Oxford.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 23 July, Oxford, Abingdon, Kidlington and Bladon were affected; some 3,000 homes including the home of William Morris at Kelmscott were flooded and 600 residents were evacuated, with many taking refuge in Oxford United Football Club's Kassam Stadium.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 24 July, the Thames in Abingdon rose 3 feet (0.9 m) in less than 12 hours to a "perilously high" level and the Thames and the Severn were expected to rise to 20 feet (6.1 m) higher than normal.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 25 July, residents of Osney in west Oxford were advised to leave their homes.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] About 30 people went to the Kassam stadium shelter while another 250 decided to stay with family and friends.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Osney Mead substation, which supplies power to Oxford city centre, was threatened but did not flood.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Later that evening the Thames breached its banks at Henley.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 19 June, rain had washed away the main road at Hampton Loade and the Severn Valley Railway line from Bridgnorth was closed after numerous landslips on the line.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Also, on 19 June/20 June, parts of the town of Shifnal near Telford were flooded when the Wesley Brook burst its banks.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Some of the residents blamed Severn Trent Water for opening floodgates at Priors Lee balancing lake, but no such gates existed.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Repair costs to the railway were estimated at £2 million.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 26 June, the Burway Bridge collapsed, disrupting one of the main roads into Ludlow, severing a gas main and causing the surrounding area to be evacuated.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 1 July, a woman was pulled out of the River Severn at Jackfield on the Telford and Wrekin border near Ironbridge.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 24 July, the UK National Ballooning Championships in Ludlow had been cancelled for the first time in their 32-year history.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 21 July, flooded parts of Warwickshire included Alcester, Stratford-upon-Avon, Shipston on Stour and Water Orton.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] To a lesser extent, areas of Leamington Spa and Warwick also experienced flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Several nature reserves in the Tame Valley, including Ladywalk and Kingsbury Water Park were badly affected, just as ground- and reedbed- nesting birds were hatching young.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] 200 people were forced to leave Witton Road and Tame Road in Aston, Birmingham when the River Tame flooded.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Water entered the streets of Shirley, Solihull.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] As in Warwickshire, the Tame caused losses at a nature reserve; this time RSPB Sandwell Valley.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In the Dudley borough, flooding damaged local schools, shops and communities.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Schools opened their doors with parts of buildings flooded with water; damage in the West Midlands area was estimated at £1.9 billion (2007 GDP).
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 20 July, Swindon had a month's rainfall in less than half a day.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] More than 50 people were rescued from their flooded homes.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 19 June, Worcestershire was affected by flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A 68-year-old motorist (Judge Eric Dickinson) died after becoming trapped in his vehicle in flood water near Pershore whilst attempting to cross an old ford in Bow Brook which was by then 2 m deep.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The waters were still rising, endangering the confluence of the River Teme and the River Severn.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 26 June 2007 the New Road Ground, home to Worcestershire County Cricket Club, was flooded after the River Severn overtopped its banks, causing the next day's Twenty20 match against Warwickshire to be cancelled.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 17 July, Tenbury Wells in Worcestershire was flooded for the second time in three weeks after a thunderstorm caused flash flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 21 July the M5 was affected, compounded by the closure of the Strensham services, and the motorway was closed, stranding hundreds in their vehicles overnight.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 23 July, parts of Worcestershire were under 6 feet (2 m) of water and the Army was brought in to help emergency services supply the inhabitants of Upton-upon-Severn which was cut off by floodwater.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 1 June, the first day of the floods, a road in Cropthorne near Worcester was brutally forced down by a high impact of water flowing underneath the road in a pipe.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The hole it made was 13 feet (4.0 m) deep and 33 feet (10 m) wide, traffic throughout the county was held up due to the collapsed main road.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 June, the region was hit by flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 25 June, the region was hit by flooding again.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The new Hull police station had to be vacated because of flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The next day, only 12 of Hull's 88 schools were still open, affecting 30,000 out of 38,000 Hull schoolchildren.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 4 July in Hull, six schools were still closed and 120 residents in residential or nursing care had been relocated.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 5 July, an estimated 35,000 people in streets containing 17,000 homes had been affected by flooding in Hull and by the next day more than 10,000 homes had been evacuated.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Hull City Council estimated repair costs at £200 million.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 24 July, Hull City Council had checked each house in the flooded streets and stated that 6,500 homes had been flooded.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 27 July, £2.1 million had been allocated to Hull and £600,000 to the East Riding for clean-up and immediate repairs, and £3.2 million to Hull and £1.5 million to the East Riding for further repairs to the region's estimated 101 schools suffering significant flood damage.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 3 September, figures released by Hull City Council had been revised upwards to 7,800 houses that had been flooded plus 1,300 businesses that were affected.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 15 June, towns and villages in North Yorkshire were flooded, with Knaresborough, Harrogate and York being particularly affected.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The A59 road at Kex Gill was closed due to a landslip where 100 tonnes (110 tons) of earth slid down the hillside and trapped a couple in their car.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In Scarborough, the main A171 Scalby Road flooded outside Scarborough Hospital, and the ornamental lake at Peasholm Park overtopped its banks and poured down Peasholm Gap into North Bay.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Near Catterick, North Yorkshire, a 17-year-old soldier on a training exercise from Catterick Garrison died after being swept away whilst crossing Risedale Beck, Hipswell Moor.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 23 June, flooding affected Middlesbrough.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Pickering was flooded after Pickering Beck overflowed its banks.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Pensioners were stranded in the town's swimming pool and rescued by lifeboat.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 25 June, Sheffield suffered extensive damage as the River Don overtopped its banks, causing widespread flooding in the Don Valley area of the city.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A 14-year-old boy was swept away by the swollen River Sheaf, a 68-year-old man died after attempting to cross a flooded road in Sheffield city centre, and several cattle were washed away, found up to 3.5 miles (5.6 km) across fields in some areas of cultivated land.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Meadowhall shopping centre was closed due to flooding with some shops remaining closed downstairs until late September and Sheffield Wednesday's ground Hillsborough was under 6 feet (1.83 m) of water.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A number of people were rescued by RAF helicopters from buildings in the Brightside area, while in the Millhouses Park area to the southwest of the city the River Sheaf overtopped its banks causing widespread damage.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] There was also widespread flooding in Barnsley, Doncaster and Rotherham, with much of these towns cut off.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] By 26 June, the waters in some parts of Sheffield and the surrounding area receded, and over 700 villagers from Catcliffe, near Rotherham's Ulley reservoir were evacuated after cracks appeared in the dam.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Emergency services from across England pumped millions of gallons of water from the reservoir to ease the pressure on the damaged dam, and the nearby M1 Motorway was closed between junctions 32 and 36 as a precaution.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 27 June, the Army moved into the Doncaster area after the River Don overtopped its banks and threatened the area around what was Thorpe Marsh Power Station.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] A man was incorrectly reported missing near the village of Adwick le Street near Doncaster.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 June and on 25 June, the villages of Scissett and Clayton West and other parts of Kirklees were flooded by the River Dearne, the second time worse than the first.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Six elderly women, including a 91-year-old, were stranded in their homes.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] During the Wakefield flood, hundreds of homes were evacuated in the Agbrigg area of Wakefield and looting was feared, but by 1 July only four looters had been arrested in the city and were later released on bail.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The village of Collingham (near Wetherby) was particularly affected by the flooding, and one house was looted.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Wales was hit by flooding in June and July, with the Eastern areas most badly affected.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] It was Wales's wettest June since 1998, and its second wettest since 1914.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The preserved counties and principal areas affected are given below.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 26 June, roads including the A5 were impassable at Corwen in Denbighshire, a river overflowed at Worthenbury in Flintshire, and properties were affected in Wrexham.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In North Wales, a man was rescued by fire services after he was stranded on a small island in the River Dee in Llangollen, Denbighshire.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 17 July, flash floods after torrential rain forced the closure of a secondary school in Prestatyn in Denbighshire.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Lampeter in Ceredigion was affected by flooding on 11 June and then again on 15 June.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 26 June, properties were affected in Tintern on the River Wye in Monmouthshire.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 20 July, flash floods affected parts of Newport, Monmouthshire and Torfaen.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In Radnorshire, 30 tonnes of debris and earth blocked the only road out of Barland near Presteigne on 23 July.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In Brecknockshire, the River Wye burst its banks in Builth Wells on 1 July, the saturated ground later causing chaos at the Royal Welsh Show in Llanelwedd on 24 July.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 20 July, flash floods affected the Vale of Glamorgan, causing schools to be evacuated, roads to be closed, and boats used to rescue people from their homes in Barry.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Northern Ireland was hit by flooding in the June and July floods and it was Northern Ireland's wettest June since 1958.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The non-administrative counties and districts affected are given below.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 June, the Knockmore campus of the Lisburn Institute in Lisburn was affected by flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 2 July, houses were flooded and two people evacuated from their home in Cushendall in Antrim after the River Dall burst its banks following heavy rain.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 16 July, parts of Belfast International Airport near Aldergrove in Antrim were flooded by a freak thunderstorm leaving 10 planes unable to land, landslides closed the Antrim Coast Road near Ballygally, Larne, and people were trapped in their cars in Portrush, Coleraine.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 15 June, there was severe flooding around Bangor in North Down, Saintfield, Crossgar and Ballynahinch in Down and Newtownards and Comber in Ards, with shops in Crossgar centre flooded.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 June, Magherafelt was affected by flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 16 July, roads in Aghadowey, Coleraine and Portstewart, Coleraine were rendered impassable by floodwater.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 June, Omagh and Dungannon were affected by flooding, with a Dunnes supermarket evacuated in Omagh.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Scotland was hit by flooding in June and July, with the Scottish Lowlands most badly affected.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 12 June, the Met Office issued torrential rain warnings for Scotland and it was Scotland's wettest June since 1938.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The non-administrative counties and council areas affected are given below.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 21 June, about 2000 homes were left without electricity and properties were affected as flash floods hit Kilmarnock.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 18 July, flooding affected Kilmarnock again, the River Irvine burst its banks in Newmilns, and flash floods affected roads including the M77.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 18 July, floods wrecked homes in Closeburn, power was cut off at Eaglesfield, and roads were closed at Moffat and Lochmaben.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 1 July, rain cancelled the one-day international cricket match between Scotland and Pakistan in Edinburgh and by 3 July parts of Midlothian were flooded, the worst-hit areas including residential areas in Dalkeith and Mayfield.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 22 June, heavy storms flooded roads and dumped debris on the railway line in Glasgow.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The same day, torrential rain caused a landslide just south of Lesmahagow, closing the M74.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 3 July, a landslide caused by floodwater disrupted traffic on the A941 Rothes to Aberlour road in Moray.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 25 June rain forced the 108-year-old Beltane Festival in Peebles to be held indoors for the first time.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Following the flooding in late June, the rescue effort was described by the Fire Brigades Union as the "biggest in peacetime Britain".
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Following the flooding in July, the RAF said it was carrying out its biggest-ever peacetime rescue operation, with six Sea King helicopters from as far afield as RAF St Mawgan in Cornwall, RAF Valley in Anglesey and RAF Leconfield in the East Riding of Yorkshire rescuing up to 120 people.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] An RAF heavy lift Chinook helicopter was also employed to move aggregate to reinforce the banks of the River Don.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Environment Agency described the situation as "critical".
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] 4x4 Response groups from throughout the UK assisted councils and blue light services during and in the immediate aftermath of the flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] During the recovery phase a number of responders from around the UK 4x4 Response assisted the Red Cross in the distribution of fresh drinking water in the Gloucestershire area after mains drinking water was contaminated.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Health Protection Agency advised people that the risk of contracting any illness was low but that it was best to avoid coming into direct contact with flood water.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] There were no reported cases of any outbreaks.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In some areas bottled water was handed out where sewage works got flooded.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The floods caused widespread crop damage, especially broccoli, carrots, peas and potatoes.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In parts of Lincolnshire it was estimated that 40% of the pea crop may have been damaged, with other crops also suffering major losses.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Prices of vegetables were expected to rise in the following months.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Environment Agency chief executive Baroness Young said that about £1 billion a year was needed to improve flood defences.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Association of British Insurers has estimated the total bill for the June and July floods as £3 billion.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 3 July, Environment Secretary Hilary Benn announced that the Government would increase the spending on risk management and flood defences by £200 million to £800 million by 2010–11.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] During Prime Minister's Questions in the House of Commons later that month, Prime Minister Gordon Brown promised £46 million in aid to flood-hit councils and £800 million rise in annual spending on flood protection by 2010–11, confirming Hilary Benn's announcement.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Brown also pledged to push insurance firms to make payouts.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 22 July, the Government convened COBRA to co-ordinate the response to the crisis.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Visiting Gloucestershire on 25 July, Mr.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Brown praised emergency services for their efforts, but added: "We've got to get the supplies stepped up.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 8 August 2007, Defra announced that Sir Michael Pitt would chair an independent review of the response to the flooding.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] On 4 September of that year the Cabinet Office website launched a comments page to let people affected by the flooding contribute their experiences to the review.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Sir Michael published his interim report on 17 December 2007.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In April 2010 the government passed the Flood and Water Management Act 2010, which implemented many of Sir Michael Pitt's recommendations.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In also brings in a new regime whereby new building activity which exacerbates flooding by reducing the capacity of land to absorb water will need to be accompanied by the construction of sustainable drainage systems such as grassy roofs, ponds and soakaways.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Hull City Council was criticised for not insuring the city's libraries, schools and other public buildings.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In response, Hull City Council said that "Many councils do not have the feature in their budget", but other flood-hit councils were insured.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] It was thought that council tax payers would be left with the bill, as emergency Government funding would not cover it.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In June, councillors in Hull claimed that the city was being forgotten and had the floods occurred in the Home Counties, help would have arrived much more quickly.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] One in five homes in Hull was damaged and 90 out of the city's 105 schools suffered some damage.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Damage to the schools alone was estimated to cost £100 million.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The Bellwin scheme for providing aid after natural disasters was criticised as inadequate by Hull MP Diana Johnson.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] The lack of media coverage of flooding in Kingston upon Hull led the city council leader Carl Minns to dub Hull "the forgotten city".
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In July, the Government came under mounting criticism of its handling of the crisis, the fact that responsibilities were spread across four departments and no single minister could be held responsible, and the fact that the Army had not been called in to assist.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] In response to the criticism, Environment Secretary Hilary Benn said on BBC *Sunday AM* that "This was very, very intense rainfall, with five inches in 24 hours in some areas; even some of the best defences are going to be overwhelmed".
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] He praised the way the emergency services had dealt with "unprecedented" levels of rainfall and said he had "total confidence" in the response of the Environment Agency.
[src:gloucester/2007-united-kingdom-floods] Conservative leader David Cameron called for a public inquiry into the flooding after visiting Witney, the main town in his Oxfordshire constituency.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The **2015 Rugby World Cup** was the eighth Rugby World Cup, the quadrennial rugby union world championship.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The tournament was hosted by England from 18 September to 31 October.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Of the 20 countries competing in the World Cup in 2011, there was only one change: Uruguay replaced Russia.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] This was the first World Cup with no new teams to the tournament.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Reigning champions The All Blacks won the cup and defended their title by defeating Australia 34–17 in the final; South Africa defeated Argentina to take third place.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] This was the first Rugby World Cup where no Northern Hemisphere team got beyond the quarter-finals.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] New Zealand were the first team to retain their title and the first to win for a third time.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The highly contested match between Japan and South Africa on the opening weekend, in which Japan scored the winning try in the final minute, was widely considered the biggest upset in the history of international rugby.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Hosts England were eliminated at the pool stage, after defeats by Wales and Australia; this was the first time the knockout stage did not feature a host nation.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The International Rugby Board (IRB) requested that any member unions wishing to host this tournament or the 2019 Rugby World Cup should indicate their interest by 15 August 2008.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] This would be purely to indicate interest; no details had to be provided at this stage.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] A record 10 unions indicated formal interest in hosting the 2015 and/or the 2019 events: Australia, England, Ireland, Italy, Jamaica, Japan, Russia, Scotland, South Africa and Wales.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Argentina had been reported in early 2008 as having given preliminary consideration to bidding, but did not ultimately formally indicate an interest in bidding.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Of the 10 nations that had expressed formal interest, many withdrew their candidacy in early 2009.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Jamaica was the first to withdraw its candidacy.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Russia withdrew in February 2009 to concentrate on bidding for the 2013 Rugby World Cup Sevens, Australia and Ireland withdrew in spring 2009 due to financial reasons.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Scotland withdrew in April 2009 after they were unable to secure co-hosting partners for the tournament.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Wales was the last nation to officially pull out after they failed to submit a bid by 8 May 2009, but Wales backed England's bid and some games were played at Cardiff's Millennium Stadium.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The final nations that bid for the right to host the 2015 Rugby World Cup were England, Japan, South Africa and Italy.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Four confirmed bids was a record number for the Rugby World Cup.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] On 28 July 2009, the IRB confirmed that England would host the 2015 Rugby World Cup, and Japan would host the 2019 event, having voted 16–10 in favour of approving the recommendation from Rugby World Cup Ltd (RWCL) that England and Japan should be named hosts.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] RWCL chairman Bernard Lapasset revealed the result on 28 July 2009 at IRB headquarters.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] In September 2007, *The Guardian* reported that the Rugby Football Union had decided to submit a bid.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] BBC News reported in February 2009 that the intent was for a solo bid from the RFU, but with the possibility of some matches being played in Scotland, Wales or Ireland.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] It was hoped that the 2015 World Cup would add to Britain's "Decade of Sport" (including the 2012 Summer Olympics, 2013 Rugby League World Cup and 2014 Commonwealth Games).
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] It was also claimed that the bid had a very strong chance of success due to the IRB's belief that the 2011 tournament might make a loss, therefore making it particularly important to ensure a profit, which was considered a strong point of England's proposed bid.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The chief executive of the Rugby Football Union, Francis Baron, said that the tournament would target sales of 3 million tickets.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] England's package was projected to generate £300 million for the IRB – £220 million in commercial returns from broadcasting, sponsorship and merchandising, and the £80 million tournament fee.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Italy stated its desire to host, and an Italian bid to host the Rugby World Cup in 2015 or 2019 was confirmed on 20 July 2008.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Italy declared that it wanted to host "For the Enlargement of the Frontiers of Our Sport".
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] It was a slogan relevant to the then-current landscape of World Cup rugby, given that 2007 was the first time that the Rugby World Cup was hosted by a primarily non-English-speaking country.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The Italian bid offered the largest cities and stadiums in the country and promised a fast domestic train system.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The Italian Rugby Federation (FIR) also included the importance of the population and the growth of rugby since Italy joined the Six Nations in 2000 as reasons for hosting a World Cup.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Rugby had been growing increasingly popular in Italy in recent years, with improved crowds at international matches.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The Stadio Olimpico in Rome had been proposed as the venue to host the final and the first match of the tournament.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Milan and Naples were included as the other large venues.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The entire list was a selection of large stadiums spread across the country.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Stade Vélodrome in Marseille, France was also included as the tenth proposed venue.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The Japan Rugby Football Union officially submitted its tender to the IRB in May 2009.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Japan was seen as a favourite to host after finishing as runner-up in the bidding for the 2011 event.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Japan was seen as having a lot to offer rugby's growth in Asia.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Its population of 127 million, its large economy, and its ability to place rugby before a new Asian audience made it a front-runner for hosting rights.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Furthermore, rugby in Japan had developed a following, and with 126,000 registered players, Japan had more players than some of the Six Nations.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Japan's Top League was a showcase for Japanese rugby, and there was excitement about Japan's entry into the RWC.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Japan's experience in co-hosting the 2002 FIFA World Cup was also seen as a boost, with Japan already possessing the necessary stadiums and infrastructure.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The South African Rugby Union (SARU) had confirmed its intent to bid for the 2015 tournament, and in May 2009 South Africa delivered its application to the IRB.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] South Africa had previously made an unsuccessful bid to host the 2011 RWC.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] After England were appointed tournament hosts on 28 July 2009, the proposed stadia for the tournament were revealed.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The final venues were confirmed, along with the tournament's schedule, on 2 May 2013.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Twelve of the stadia were located in England, while the Millennium Stadium located in neighbour Wales was also to be used.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] In 2011, the IRB approved the use of the Millennium Stadium, despite being outside of the host country, due to its capacity and strategic location.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Of the thirteen venues, two were dedicated rugby union grounds (Kingsholm Stadium and Sandy Park), two were national rugby stadia (Twickenham and the Millennium Stadium), two were multi-purpose stadia (Wembley Stadium and the Olympic Stadium), and the remainder were association football grounds.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Proposed venues that did not make the final selection were the Stadium of Light in Sunderland, Coventry's Ricoh Arena, St Mary's Stadium in Southampton, Pride Park Stadium in Derby, Anfield in Liverpool and Bristol's Ashton Gate.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] In April 2013, Old Trafford was withdrawn from consideration by its owners, Manchester United F.C., citing commitments to hosting rugby league and its Super League Grand Final and concerns about pitch degradation.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The RWCL then approached neighbouring Manchester City about leasing their home stadium as a replacement.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] City agreed to let their stadium be used for the tournament but only for one match due to footballing commitments – down from the original three which were to be played at Old Trafford.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Etihad Stadium, as it was known for football sponsorship purposes, would be called 'Manchester City Stadium' by organisers for the duration of the tournament.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The 41 venues that acted as bases for the teams were announced on 26 August 2014.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] All prospective team bases were subject to a rigorous selection process, which included a programme of detailed site visits as well as liaison with the competing teams.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Each team base included an outdoor and indoor training facility, a swimming pool, gym and hotel and would be used by the competing teams in the lead up to and during the World Cup.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Of the 20 teams competing at the 2015 World Cup, 12 of them qualified by finishing in the top three places in their pools in the 2011 Rugby World Cup.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The other eight teams qualified through regional competition.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] As the host nation, England qualified automatically.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The qualification process for the remaining teams incorporated existing regional competitions such as the European Nations Cup.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Twenty teams played in the final tournament.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] They are listed below, along with their pre-tournament positions in the World Rugby Rankings.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The list of teams was the same as in the 2003 tournament.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Seedings for the pools of the 2015 World Cup were based on the teams' respective IRB Rankings.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The draw, hosted by Will Greenwood, was conducted on 3 December 2012 in London, and used the World Rankings as of that day, just after the 2012 end-of-year rugby union internationals, which finished on 1 December 2012.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The draw saw a representative randomly draw a ball from a pot, the first drawn ball goes to Pool A, the second Pool B, the third Pool C and the fourth Pool D.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The timing of the draw drew criticism due to the long period between the draw occurring and the commencement of the tournament – three years.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Indeed, by the time of the pool match between England and Wales on 26 September, pool A contained the 2nd, 3rd and 4th (Australia, England and Wales) ranked teams in the world.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] That's just ridiculous as far as I am concerned.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] If they had followed the football model, then we wouldn't be in this position.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] There are other people outside this who need to have a look at themselves and why those decisions were made, and you have got to feel sorry for the people involved and who this has affected".
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The chief executive of World Rugby Brett Gosper subsequently acknowledged criticisms, saying "We'll look at that next time to see if it's possible to make the draw closer to the tournament".
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Each country was allowed a squad of 31 players for the tournament.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] These squads were to be submitted to World Rugby by a deadline of 31 August 2015.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Once the squad was submitted, a player could be replaced if injured, but would not be allowed to return to the squad.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] There was also a stand-down period of 48 hours before the new player was allowed to take the field.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Hence, a replacement player called into a squad on the eve of a game would not be permitted to play in that game.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The opening ceremony of the 2015 Rugby World Cup took place at Twickenham Stadium in London on 18 September 2015 at 19:20 (BST).
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The ceremony told the legend of how William Webb Ellis created the sport of rugby union, and featured the choir of Rugby School singing "Swing Low, Sweet Chariot", an anthem of rugby union in England.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] All the participating teams were represented by a former player in the ceremony; the host nation, England, was represented by World Cup-winning captain Martin Johnson.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The ceremony was directed by Kim Gavin, who was also responsible for directing the closing ceremonies of both the 2012 Summer Olympics and the 2012 Summer Paralympics.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex, who had an acting part previously in the ceremony, declared the tournament officially open, ending his speech with the words, "We're ready.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Game on." British Prime Minister David Cameron said on social media that the 2015 Rugby World Cup would be the best ever.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The first round, or pool stage, saw the 20 teams divided into four pools of five teams, using the same format that was used in 2003, 2007, and 2011.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Each pool was a single round-robin of ten games, in which each team played one match against each of the other teams in the same pool.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Teams were awarded four points for a win, two points for a draw and none for a defeat.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] A team scoring four tries in one match scored a bonus point, as did a team that lost by fewer than eight points.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The teams finishing in the top two of each pool would advance to the quarter-finals.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The top three teams of each pool received automatic qualification to the 2019 Rugby World Cup (Japan had already automatically qualified as hosts).
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Official World Rugby Rankings as of 12 October 2015.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] If three teams were tied on points, the above criteria would be used to decide first place in the Pool, and then the criteria would be used again (starting from criteria 1) to decide second place in the Pool.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] At the 2015 World Rugby Awards, Japan's game-winning final try against South Africa was named the best match moment of the tournament.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] A dream team was named made up of the best performing players of the tournament.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The tournament's top point scorer was Argentine fly-half Nicolás Sánchez, who scored 97 points.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] New Zealand wing Julian Savea scored the most tries, eight, equalling the record for one tournament set by his compatriot Jonah Lomu and South African Bryan Habana.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] ITV Sport was the UK and worldwide host broadcaster for the 2015 event, having signed a deal in 2011 to broadcast the 2011 and 2015 RWC tournaments.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] ITV won the rights after outbidding rivals including the BBC and Sky Sports.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] It showed every match from the tournament live in the UK on ITV or ITV4.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] The officially licensed *Rugby World Cup 2015* video game was released on 4 September 2015 on PC, PS3, PS4, PS Vita, Xbox 360 and Xbox One.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] IGN rated the game 1.5/10, calling it "unbearable to play".
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Ticket prices were announced in November 2013 with general sale applications launching in September 2014.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Adult ticket prices started at £15 for pool matches and children's tickets were available from £7 at 41 of the 48 matches.
[src:gloucester/2015-rugby-world-cup] Tickets for the final ranged from £150 to £715.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The **2021–2022 United Kingdom censuses** collectively comprised the 23rd census of the United Kingdom.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses of England and Wales, and Northern Ireland took place on 21 March 2021, and the census of Scotland took place later on 20 March 2022.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses were administered by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) in England and Wales, by the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) in Northern Ireland, and by the National Records of Scotland in Scotland.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] These were the first UK censuses for which most of the data was gathered online.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Two of the censuses went ahead despite the COVID-19 pandemic, in part because the information obtained would assist government and public understanding of the pandemic's impact.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census in Scotland was postponed, and took place in 2022.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The censuses in 2021 and 2022 follow on from Beyond 2011, a project by the UK Statistics Authority to assess the value, cost, and alternatives to running a census in England and Wales in 2021.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The project recommended an England and Wales census be held in 2021, and that it be conducted predominantly by means of online returns.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial results for England and Wales were released on 28 June 2022, while initial results for Scotland were released on 14 September 2023.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] After the 2011 census, both the UK coalition government and the main opposition party, Labour, expressed concerns about the rising costs of the decadal census.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] There were also concerns about the value of continuing with the traditional approach adopted for the 2011 census.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] This included whether collection methods were still fit for purpose in a rapidly changing society and whether census outputs, based on a survey conducted every ten years, would continue to meet the increasingly demanding needs of public and private sector users.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Emerging technological developments were seen as providing alternative and improved data gathering opportunities.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] These concerns and opportunities led the UK Government to question if a supplementary or wholly alternative approach to the traditional 10-yearly census was required; more frequent, possibly annual, small-scale surveys could be employed instead.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] In 2011, The Beyond 2011 Programme was established to look at alternatives to the traditional census approach.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority coordinated the project which was also undertaken by its counterparts in the devolved administrations of Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Existing census gathering methods would be used only as an alternative, where online methods are not feasible.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] A parallel announcement for Scotland's 2021 census was made by the National Records for Scotland.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The ONS Director, Population and Demography Statistics was reported as saying that an estimated 60–65% of household returns would be completed online.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] In April 2014, the British House of Commons Public Accounts Committee (PAC) concluded in its report *Too soon to scrap the Census*, that the 2021 census should go ahead.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] It had reservations over the lack of investigation into the options for using administrative data and encouraged the UK Government to reassure the public about privacy concerns.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Minister for the Cabinet Office welcomed the recommendations for a predominantly online 2021 census for England and Wales supplemented by the use of governmental and other administrative data in a letter to the National Statistician in July 2014.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Under the Census Act 1920, it is for the United Kingdom Government and Parliament to determine the arrangements for census-taking in England and Wales.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Parallel legislative procedures will be required in the devolved administrations of Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] It would be late 2015 at the earliest before regulations were made.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Subject to this legislation being passed the census would be conducted on the same day in England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland to ensure coherence and consistency.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] There is a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] As at 21 March 2021 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Failure to return a completed questionnaire could lead to a fine and criminal record.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, the Census (Amendment) (Scotland) Act 2019 made provisions for voluntary questions about transgender status and sexual orientation to be asked.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Census (Return Particulars and Removal of Penalties) Act 2019 makes the same provision for England and Wales.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The sexual orientation question would also be asked in Northern Ireland.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The campaign 'If you're not religious, say so!' by Humanists UK aimed to change the wording of the census question on religion.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] This campaign encouraged non-religious people to tick 'no religion' in order to create a more accurate portrayal of religiousness in the UK.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Another campaign by the Climate Census campaign group suggested writing in 'Climate concerned' in response to the religion question, to demand climate action from the government.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics published an online guidance titled *What is your Sex* for the 2021 census.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The guidance provided that a respondent should answer according to official documents such as their passport.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Self-identification is already recognised in some countries.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] A gender marker on a British passport can be changed in a less formal procedure than acquiring a legally enforceable gender recognition certificate.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] In March 2021, Fair Play for Women, an anti-transgender campaign group against self-identification, applied for judicial review in England and Wales and argued that such incidental self-identification should not be allowed in census-taking.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] In the absence of opposition or intervention from any interested party, the judge ordered an interim revision of the guidance.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The government conceded and accepted the order.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The ONS withdrew from the High Court proceedings.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Some academics criticised what they said was the ONS's confusion between the concepts of sex and gender identity.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Other academics supported the design of the census questions, for example, on the ground that the transgender population is very small.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, similar pieces of guidance have been published since the previous census in 2011.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Scottish Parliament also sought to amend the census Act in 2019 to clarify the meaning of sex in that legislation to include gender identity.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The plan was abandoned and changes were instead made in subordinate legislation.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] In August 2021, National Records of Scotland issued guidelines regarding the sex question in the 2022 Scottish census.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The guidance states that "If you are transgender the answer you give can be different from what is on your birth certificate.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] You do not need a Gender Recognition Certificate (GRC)".
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority wrote to National Records of Scotland to question the guidelines.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] In December 2021, Fair Play for Women applied for a judicial review in Scotland.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Lord Sandison dismissed the case on 17 February 2022 stating that there was "no general rule or principle of law that a question as to a person's sex may only properly be answered by reference to the sex stated on that person's birth certificate or GRC".
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] An appeal by Fair Play for Women was refused by the Inner House of the Court of Session.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority has the responsibility for coordinating the census arrangements across the United Kingdom through the Office for National Statistics (ONS), which is also responsible for the census in England and Wales.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 UK census was the first decennial census in the United Kingdom to include the option of completing the census documentation online.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Across the UK between 15 and 19% of census forms were submitted online.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority proposed that the 2021 census should be conducted predominantly online (with support provided for those unable to complete the census online), supplemented by the use of administrative and survey data and improve annual statistics between censuses.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] For the census in 2021 the proposed target for online completion has been set to at least 65%.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Research has been under way since 2011 to design a new census methodology which maximises the success of an online approach.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Issues identified also included the accuracy of administrative data sets for geographical areas below that of local authorities, problems associated with estimation and the use of address registers.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The UK Statistics Authority has commissioned research strands as part of a census transformation programme which was due to report by 2017 relating to the 2021 census operation, the shape of population statistics in 2021, and the shape of population statistics beyond 2021 in the lead up to 2031.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] A work programme running until 2024, comprising eight phases, was developed by ONS.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Alongside this programme trials of statistics generation using administrative data were planned starting from the autumn of 2015 and running through to 2021 with the aim of ranging across the breadth, detail and accuracy of census outputs.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The contract for preparing, dispatching up to 16 million paper questionnaire packs (for anyone who did not want to, or could not access the census online), and then securely managing, capturing and digitising the responses was awarded to Leidos Innovations UK.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The contract was estimated to be worth around £65.1m.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The parent company of Leidos Innovations UK, Leidos (an American defence, aviation, information technology, and biomedical research company), merged with Lockheed Martin's IT sector in August 2016.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK was awarded the contract for the census in 2011.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Adecco UK was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 30,000 temporary ONS workers who would be working as field staff for the 2021 census.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] An advertising campaign (made under contract by M&C Saatchi) was launched under the slogan of "it's about us" at the start of 2021.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Television adverts tried to show a diverse range of people in various locations in England and Wales in front of a purple fabric screen, with a cover version of The Zombies' "This Will Be Our Year", performed by Jose McGill & The Vagaband, featuring as the advert soundtrack.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) undertakes the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The National Records of Scotland (NRS) is responsible for the census in Scotland.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal was conducted on 7 October 2019 and closed for returns on 7 November 2019 in three local authority areas: parts of Glasgow City, Dumfries and Galloway and Na h-Eileanan Siar.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census was scheduled to take place on 21 March 2021, but was delayed in July 2020 by the Scottish Government because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Scottish Government has come under criticism for the way the census has been conducted, with some news outlets describing the results as being "botched" due to record low turnout rates and failing to meet the set target return rate of 94%.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial turnout rates for the census in Scotland concluded with 79% return rate; an additional round of extension to filling out the census was granted to encourage returns, raising the return rate percentage to 89%.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The return rate for comparison in England and Wales was 97%.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] However national statistician Ian Diamond has said that despite not meeting the target, the census could still provide "really good data".
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The additional round of extension cost the Scottish Government an additional £6m, and £148m in total.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Although it is a Crown Dependency and not part of the United Kingdom, Jersey carried out a census on the same day as the 2021 censuses in England and Wales, and Northern Ireland.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Guernsey no longer carries out a decennial census, instead using the Rolling Electronic Census Project to produce regular census reports.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Isle of Man also undertook a full census in 2021 (having held an interim census in 2016).
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Initial results, released in June 2022, showed the recorded population of England and Wales to be 59,597,300 (56,489,800 in England and 3,107,500 in Wales), a rise of 6.3% or 3.5 million people over the previous decade.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] This was the largest population ever recorded through a census in England and Wales, and the overall population of the United Kingdom was estimated to be 67 million.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census also showed that the population of the two countries, aged 65 and over, had surpassed the number of children aged 15 and under for the first time, with 11.1 million people aged 65 and over compared with 10.4 million aged under 15.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results of the question on religion were published on 29 November 2022.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The question was voluntary but was answered by 94.0% of the population of England and Wales.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] 46.2% of the population described themselves as "Christian", 6.5% as "Muslim", and 1.7% as "Hindu".
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] 37.2% of the population asserted that they had "no religion".
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] In Wales, there were more people declaring that they had "no religion" (47%) than those affirming a Christian identity or any other religion.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results on sexual orientation and gender identity questions were released on 6 January 2023.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Similarly to the religion question, this question was voluntary but was answered by 92.5% of the population of England and Wales.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] 89.4% of the population described themselves as straight or heterosexual, 1.5% described themselves as "Gay or lesbian", 1.3% as "Bisexual" and 0.3% were described as having "[an]other sexual orientation" (with the most common being pansexual, asexual and queer).
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] 0.5% answered 'No' to the census question 'Is the gender you identify with the same as your sex registered at birth?' Alice Sullivan, professor of sociology at University College London, reported that in the 16 to 24 age group, 1% answered 'No' to the question.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] She said that females were more likely than males to answer 'No' in that age group, whereas in other age groups females were more likely to answer 'Yes'.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] In April 2023, when more granular data became available, Michael Biggs, professor of sociology at the University of Oxford, complained about what he perceived to be anomalies in the data on the 0.5% who identified as transgender, when disaggregated by local authority and other factors.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] He questioned whether the ONS had adequately tested the gender identity question with respondents for whom English is a second language.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The Office for Statistics Regulation (OSR), which oversees the ONS, began an examination of Biggs' concerns about the statistics, including the reported result that 262,000 identify as transgender in England and Wales.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] An anonymous government source said they believed the number 260,000 of transgender people was "hugely overstated".
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] In September 2024, the OSR removed official accreditation of the gender identity statistics, classifying them instead as official statistics in development.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Results for Northern Ireland were published by the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency in Spring 2023.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] National Records of Scotland published the first results on 14 September 2023.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The results showed that Scotland's population was 5,436,600, the highest figure on record but a slower rate of population growth, 2.7% since 2011, than the previous growth of 4.6%.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The first results, in May 2024, were population estimates at output areas, as well as topical data about ethnic group, national identity, language and religion.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The rest of the data was published across 2024 and into 2025.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The low response rates (88%) compared with the rest of the UK mean that the data is only partial so does not fully reflect the state of Scotland's demographics.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census showed there were 2,509,300 households in Scotland with at least one usual resident.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] There were some 930,000 single person households in Scotland and over a third of all households were single person (37.1%).
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census revealed that over half a million people living in Scotland were born in the rest of the UK (563,500).
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Furthermore, that a further half a million were born outside of the UK (554,900).
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The number of people born outside of the UK had increased by 185,600 since 2011.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The census showed the population as ageing, with over one million people aged 65 and over (1,091,000).
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The number of people under 15 was only 832,300.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] The majority of people said they had no religion.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Of those who were religious in 2022, 20.4% responded ‘Church of Scotland', 13.3% ‘Roman Catholic’, 5.1% 'Other Christian' and 2.2% 'Muslim'.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] Among those who selected 'Other Christian,' 72,359 people identified as Anglican or Episcopalian.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] In 2022 the census results showed 12.9% of people in Scotland had a minority ethnic background.
[src:gloucester/2021-united-kingdom-census] 77.7% described themselves as 'Scottish', 9.4% as 'Other British'.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The **A38**, parts of which are known as Devon Expressway, Bristol Road and Gloucester Road, is a major A-class trunk road in England.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The road runs from Bodmin in Cornwall to Mansfield in Nottinghamshire.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It is 292 miles (470 km) long, making it the longest two digit A road in England.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It was formerly known as the *Leeds–Exeter Trunk Road*, when this description also included the A61.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Before the opening of the M5 motorway in the 1960s and 1970s, the A38 formed the main "holiday route" from the Midlands to Somerset, Devon and Cornwall.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Considerable lengths of the road in the West Midlands closely follow Roman roads, including part of Icknield Street.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Between Worcester and Birmingham the current A38 follows the line of a Saxon salt road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] For most of the length of the M5 motorway, the A38 road runs alongside it as a single carriageway road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The road starts on the eastern side of Bodmin at a junction with the A30 before traversing the edge of the town to meet the A30 again.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It travels through the picturesque Glynn Valley to Dobwalls and Liskeard, which are bypassed by a dual carriageway.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Dobwalls section contains a bat bridge.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The A38 continues through the Cornish countryside, bypassing the centre of Saltash and continuing through the Saltash Tunnel.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Immediately after the tunnel the River Tamar is crossed using the Tamar Bridge where the route resumes dual carriageway status.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The section from Plymouth to Exeter is known locally as the Devon Expressway; it forms the southern border of Dartmoor National Park, and serves as a southward extension of the M5 motorway opening in 1977.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It is 42 miles (68 km) long and was completed in the early 1970s.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] There are several grade separated junctions along its length mainly for local traffic; including a three-level stacked roundabout interchange for the A386, which heads out towards Dartmoor National Park.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The route was reserved for the Parkway as early as 1943, when it was included in the Plan for Plymouth.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] In the early 1990s, the Marsh Mills junction was significantly remodelled, reducing the size of the roundabout and building a flyover over the top of it, allowing free flowing access from the Plympton bypass onto the Parkway.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The viaducts carrying the A38 over the River Plym, which after the construction of the Marsh Mills flyover became the Exeter bound sliproads, were built in 1969–70 as part of the Plympton bypass.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] They were replaced in the 1990s due to suffering from Alkali Silica Reaction, and the project, completed in February 1996 at a cost of £12.25 million, involved the world's largest sideways bridge slide at the time for the 410 metres (1,350 ft), 5,500 tonne bridge.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This required the road to be closed for only 48 hours, which won it an AA National Motoring Award in 1996 for innovation and minimisation of traffic congestion.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The road widens to a three-lane dual carriageway for the Plympton bypass.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This opened in 1971 and was the first section of the Devon Expressway to be built on a new alignment, as well as being the first sizeable dual carriageway section of the route.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Before Ivybridge, the route roughly parallels the original route, bypassing the village of Lee Mill which is now home to a large trading estate.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Ivybridge bypass opened in 1973 and the South Brent bypass in 1974, both on new alignments.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The A38 passes Endsleigh Garden Centre, which used to have direct access from the dual carriageway, although since the early 2000s this has been closed and the garden centre is accessed from the Westover junction for Ivybridge.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The route originally ended at the Marsh Mills roundabout, which when opened was the largest in Europe.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The section of the A38 between the A382 junction and Ashburton was built on a new alignment parallel to the old road, and was opened in 1974.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Trago Mills, a locally well known retailer, is passed by the road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Ashburton bypass, much like the Kennford bypass, uses the alignment of a much older 1930s single carriageway bypass, which was subsequently upgraded to dual carriageway by 1974.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] At the town of Buckfastleigh, the route once again bypasses on a new alignment, although due to the challenging topography of the area, the road crosses part of the town on a viaduct.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The road occupies part of the alignment of the former Totnes to Ashburton railway line.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] From Buckfastleigh to the A385 junction, the current road follows the route of original single carriageway, with the majority of this section being upgraded between 1973 and 1974, although a small section at Dean Prior was upgraded between 1966 and 1967.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This section is of a poor quality when compared to the majority of the route between Exeter and Plymouth, containing several side turnings with short exit/entry slips, and properties which back onto the road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The town of Chudleigh and the village of Chudleigh Knighton are bypassed on a new alignment, which opened in 1973, and the following section at Heathfield up to the A382 junction was upgraded from the original route between 1966 and 1968.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Some of this section follows part of the old Teign Valley Line railway.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Before Kennford, the route splits, with the A38 heading for Plymouth and the A380 heading towards Torbay.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The third lane is lost at the top of the hill, and the next section, the Harcombe bends is an original dual carriageway section, older than the rest of the route and this is evident with its sharp bends.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Devon Expressway ends near the village of Kennford, south of Exeter, at the terminus of the M5.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This initial section was opened in 1977, along with the remaining section of the M5, and is a three-lane dual carriageway.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The village of Kennford is bypassed, on an alignment of a 1930s bypass, which was upgraded to a dual-carriageway in the 1960s and then widened to a dual three-lane road in 1975.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] A junction to the south of Exeter represents a third meeting point of the A38 with the A30, from which point the A38 multiplexes with the M5 before re-emerging from junction 27 near Waterloo Cross, 21 miles (34 km) north of Exeter.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] From junction 27 the A38 heads north via Wellington, Taunton, Bridgwater, Highbridge and Bristol.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] From Waterloo Cross to Birmingham, the road is paralleled by the M5, where the A38 has reverted to taking local traffic only.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] From Bristol, it continues north via Gloucester, Tewkesbury, Worcester and Bromsgrove to Birmingham.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Between Worcester and Birmingham the A38 followed the line of an identified Saxon Salt road, one of six leading out of Droitwich.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] At Bromsgrove, it meets the M42 and the B4096 at junction 1 at Lickey End.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It passes through Upper Catshill and meets the M5 at junction 4 (along with the A491 road) near Lydiate Ash.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] From here to Edgbaston, the road is mostly dual carriageway, single-lane sections having been replaced in the first decade of the 21st century (see history section, below).
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Following completion of the Selly Oak bypass, the A38 deviates from its original route and briefly multiplexes with the A4040 outer Ring Road before forming the new bypass which is controversially named New Fosse Way.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] (The old route is designated B384 having been briefly B38).
[src:gloucester/a38-road] In the centre of Birmingham, a section of the road becomes the Aston Expressway A38(M) motorway, running from the north-eastern side of the Inner Ring Road through Aston to the junction with the M6 motorway at Gravelly Hill Interchange, better known as *Spaghetti Junction*.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The West Midlands section of the A38 is one of the areas chosen by the Highways Agency to monitor the effectiveness of driver location signs in assisting motorists to communicate their location to the emergency services.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] From Birmingham the road bypasses Sutton Coldfield and Lichfield, before taking up the route of the Roman road, Ryknild Street, (also spelt *Icknield* or *Rykneld*), as far as Derby.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] At Wychnor, the road crosses the River Trent and enters the district of East Staffordshire.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] At Barton Turn, near the B5016 junction, the road runs right alongside the Cross Country Route for around 1 mile (1.6 km).
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This railway line follows the line of the A38 from Derby to Plymouth.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] From Alrewas to Burton, the path called The Way for the Millennium follows the northbound carriageway.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] From Clay Mills, the road passes through the district of South Derbyshire, passing the grade separated junction with the A5132 for Willington.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Near Burnaston, there is a three-level stacked roundabout interchange with the A50; this junction features Derby with Burton services.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The road enters the City of Derby borough 0.5 miles (0.8 km) north of the Littleover interchange.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] For nearly 4 miles (6.4 km), the A38 forms part of Derby's outer ring road, including three roundabouts: Kingsway (or *Grand Canyon*) for the A5111; Markeaton for the A52; and Little Eaton (or *Abbey Hill*) for the A61 and B6179.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The section of road between Kingsway roundabout to just north of Markeaton is urban in nature and thus subject to a 40 mph (64 km/h) speed limit.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Originally terminating in Derby at the junction of *Babington Lane* with *St Peter's Street* (formerly the A6), the road enters the district of Amber Valley where it passes Drum Hill just north of Little Eaton and is crossed at this point by the Midshires Way and Centenary Way.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] There is a junction for the B6179 to Ripley and Belper.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] At Alfreton, there is a grade separated junction with the A61, A615 and B6179.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The section from Alfreton to the M1, the Alfreton–South Normanton Bypass, opened as the A615 in the late 1960s.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This section has a grade separated junction with the B600 for Somercotes and the Cotes Park industrial estate, and where it crosses the Nottingham spur of the Midland Main Line it enters the district of Bolsover.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] As a 1970s upgrade to the route of the A61 north of Derby (which became the B6179), the A38 bypasses Ripley passing through former opencast mining land, before joining end-on with the former A615 Alfreton bypass at Watchorn Intersection.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Into Nottinghamshire, the road bypasses Sutton-in-Ashfield, dropping to a single carriageway configuration of 1980s construction, including multiple traffic light controlled junctions – such as the Mansfield, Ashfield Regeneration Route ("MARR").
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The final section of the A38 from Sutton, past King's Mill Hospital into Mansfield, is purely urban in nature and is single carriageway, joining the A6009 in Mansfield Town Centre at the end of the route from Cornwall to the northern Midlands.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] When first designated in 1922, the A38 ran from the centre of Plymouth to Derby.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It was later extended west from Plymouth on the former route of the A389 over the Torpoint Ferry to a junction with the A30 at Bodmin.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] When the Tamar Bridge was opened in 1961, the A38 was rerouted on the former line of the A374, through Tideford, over the new bridge and through Crownhill, joining the old route at Plympton.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The old route of the A38, via Torpoint and the centre of Plymouth, was redesignated the A374.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The A38 was extended north from Derby to the M1 motorway and Mansfield in 1977, partly on the former line of the A615.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Liskeard bypass, stretching for 6 miles (10 km) from the west of Liskeard to Trerulefoot, opened in June 1976.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] A public inquiry was held for the Dobwalls bypass in February 2005, which was expected to cost £32 million.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The bottleneck was removed when the bypass, linking the existing Liskeard bypass to the current single carriageway section through the Glynn Valley opened in the Winter of 2008.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] A campaign to open this road was started by villagers in Dobwalls in 1930, but planning for building the road was not granted until 2006, the work starting on 15 November that year.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Two bat bridges and one bat house were added as the road cut through existing bat flight lines.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] After opening the Dobwall bypass experienced problems with surface water.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This led to lane closures in winter due to risk of ice.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] A major scheme to reconstruct a mile of the bypass started in September 2014 and is expected to last until May 2015.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It is thought it will cost an extra £10.6 million.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] In a separate improvement within the Glynn Valley, the Highways Agency stabilised a 840-metre (0.52 mi) section of the road near Bodmin Parkway railway station.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The work, which commenced in October 2007, was carried out to shore up the verge, which had been built on an embankment supported by dry stone walling and the root systems of large trees.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It was completed in May 2008 seeing the installation of kerbing, road drainage gulleys, safety barriers as well as increasing the verge width to allow for a new surface water drainage system.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The A38 in Devon runs between Tamar Bridge outside Plymouth and junction 31 of the M5, where the motorway ends; this section is known as the **Devon Expressway**.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It is mainly a two-lane dual carriageway which runs between Exeter and Plymouth serving as a continuation of the M5 motorway.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It is a popular route for tourists travelling to Cornwall, though those wanting to use a continuous dual carriageway route to Cornwall can use the A30 rather than using the Devon Expressway before joining the less major roads over the border in Cornwall.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It then runs concurrently with the M5 until junction 27, where it splits and enters Somerset independent but parallel to the M5.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] During the mid-1960s, small sections of the route between Plymouth and Exeter were upgraded to dual carriageway, such as those at Dean Prior and Heathfield.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This was followed by the construction of Plympton bypass in 1970–71, with the majority of realignment, such as the Ivybridge and Buckfastleigh bypasses, being completed during 1973–74.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The route, now known as the Devon Expressway, was largely complete by 1975, with the final section between Kennford and the M5 opening in 1977, coinciding with the completion of the final section of the M5 around Exeter during the same year.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Whilst many of the sections were newly constructed realignments, some sections such as the Ashburton and Kennford bypasses were upgraded from the original 1930s single carriageway bypasses.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Parkway, the section of dual carriageway through the suburbs of Plymouth between the Tamar Bridge and Marsh Mills, was constructed in 1983–84, along a route which had been reserved for this road since 1943.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This was followed by the construction of a flyover over Marsh Mills roundabout in 1992, providing a non-stop route between the Plympton bypass and the Parkway.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Plympton bypass opened in 1971, and was used for a stage in the 1974 Tour de France, with a 3.5 miles (5.6 km) stretch closed to traffic in order to allow the visit of the race to the United Kingdom.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The viaducts carrying the A38 over the River Plym, which after the construction of the Marsh Mills flyover became the Exeter bound sliproads, were built in 1969–1970 as part of the Plympton bypass.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] They were replaced in the 1990s due to suffering from Alkali Silica Reaction, and the project, completed in February 1996 at a cost of £12.25million, involved the world's largest sideways bridge slide at the time for the 410 metres (1,350 ft), 5,500 tonne bridge.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This required the road to be closed for only 48 hours, winning it an AA National Motoring Award in 1996 for innovation and minimisation of traffic congestion.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] As with any major road, accidents are likely to occur; however due to the substandard design of some sections of the route between Exeter and Plymouth, the accident rate has been identified as being above the national average for the type of road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] A spate of accidents in April 2009 heightened local awareness of the issue, with local MP Gary Streeter calling for a review of the road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] A number of improvements have been made along the route in recent years, mainly being the replacement of worn-out road surfaces, such as those at Buckfastleigh and Ivybridge.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] These projects have also included the replacement of signage, and the reconstruction of exit/entry slips for side turnings, in a bid to make the road safer.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Presently, the route between Plymouth and the end of M5 is all dual carriageway, and branded the Devon Expressway, being the primary route that links Plymouth to the rest of the country.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Beyond the end of the M5, the road runs concurrently with and as the M5 until junction 27.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] From junction 27 of the M5 to East Brent, the A38 runs broadly parallel to the motorway: junctions 22 to 27 are mostly spurs connecting to the road and all no further than 1.5 miles (2.4 km) from it.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The A38 runs around Wellington, through the county seat of Taunton, North Petherton and Highbridge.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Beyond Highbridge and junction 22, the road departs the motorway and resumes primary status, going through Winscombe, Churchill and Lower Langford where it crosses the A368 between Weston-super-Mare and Bath.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This route is the suggested route for accessing the south of Bristol and Bristol Airport from the South West.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The centre of Bridgwater was a notorious bottleneck on the "holiday route" as traffic from both the A38 and the A39 had to negotiate through the town centre in order to cross the River Parrett.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The construction of a new reinforced concrete road bridge, the Blake Bridge, which opened in March 1958 as part of a southern bypass took much of the traffic away from the centre of Bridgwater.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The opening of the M5 in 1974 further reduced the traffic pressure.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This is complemented by a link road (Western Way) linking the A38 and the A39 north and west of the town respectively.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Much of the A38 through Somerset was built as single carriageway, with some three-lane passing points.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] However, the construction of the M5 through Somerset, in the early 1970s, led to the building of links between the A38 and the M5 in the form of new roundabouts on the A38 linking into adjacent junctions on the M5.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The A38 serves Bristol Airport to the southwest of the city, and enters the city itself at Highridge, along Bedminster Down and into Bedminster.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It runs through central Bristol before leaving northwards along North Street, Stokes Croft and Gloucester Road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It runs past the former Filton Airport in South Gloucestershire to meet the M5 again at junction 16.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Thereafter it runs through Almondsbury and by-passes Thornbury to enter Gloucestershire.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] South of Bristol, the road was diverted in 2001 to cater for an extension of the runway and installation of a category 3 landing system at Bristol Airport.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The route south of the city, despite serving the airport, is single-carriageway and suffers from heavy volume of traffic at peak times, and congestion along Bedminster Down.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] From Bedminster Down the A38 follows West Street and East Street through the centre of Bedminster, but drivers from the south were advised by road signs not to follow the A38 into the city, but to use the A3029 (Winterstoke Road) to enter from the west, as this route had a greater capacity.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] As part of the *Greater Bristol Strategic Transport Study*, a link road had been under consideration to the south of Bristol.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This is in part due to the congestion at Winterstoke Road and Barrow Gurney, both of which are very busy, especially the latter where the road can only accommodate travelling at one direction at a given time; and the incomplete Bristol Ring Road (A4174).
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This road, named the South Bristol Link, was subsequently opened in 2017 and now surpasses the A3029 (Winterstoke Road) as the main route from Bristol Airport to the city centre and the motorway network north of Bristol.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] In central Bristol, the original route from Bedminster Bridge ran up Redcliffe Hill and then along Redcliff Street to Bristol Bridge.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] In the 1950s Redcliff Street was declassified, following completion of the Inner Circuit Road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It then follows Rupert Street to the St James Barton roundabout and Stokes Croft.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The route to the north of the city is also very busy: it runs as a single carriageway up to the junction with the A4174 ring road at Filton, and where it runs as Gloucester Road is a busy shopping parade.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Beyond the ring road, it runs as dual-carriageway past the site of the now-closed Filton Airport which lies in South Gloucestershire, which contains bases for Royal Mail, Airbus, Rolls-Royce and others.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Almondsbury Junction to Southmead Roundabout Improvement would cost £4,915,000 for 3 miles (4.8 km) of dual cariageway in 1975.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This improvement was first announced in April 1968, along with the M5 extension from Edithmead to Exeter, and the extension of the M32.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It opened in parts, with the last part on 31 August 1978 It was built by Sir Lindsay Parkinson & Company.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Beyond junction 16 of the M5 it runs as a broad single carriageway, again parallel to the M5 in route towards Gloucester.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The present road from Bristol through Horfield was one of the additional roads added to the Bristol turnpike roads in 1749.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This passed through Thornbury to Stone, just beyond the boundary of South Gloucestershire, where it met one of the Gloucester turnpike roads.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] From Almondsbury, the road approximately follows the line of the Roman road from Sea Mills to Gloucester.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The previous main route out of Bristol (one of twelve roads from the city, turnpiked in 1727) was Stapleton and Hambrook to the upper end of Tytherington and thence to Stone.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This seems to be parts of B4058, B4424, and then unclassified roads.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] However, Ogilby's *Britannia* shows a route following the B4058 as far as Cromhall, then through Stinchcombe Bottom, Dursley, and Cam before joining the present road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Bristol turnpike roads were continued by a turnpike road established in 1727, described as "from the City of Gloucester to the village of Stone being the great road from the north to west of this kingdom".
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Much of the road, follows a Roman road, but deviates from it between Buckover and Whitfield.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The A38 was rerouted along the Gloucester Bypass when it was built, and the old route through the city became the A430.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] In 2007 the Gloucester South Western Bypass opened to traffic, costing £43 million.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Though it is numbered A430 and not technically part of the A38, traffic wishing to continue on the A38 on the other side of the city is signed to use the bypass, rather than the existing A38.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Beyond Gloucester, the A38 was probably only improved in 1756 under an Act (29 Geo.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] 58) dealing with roads from that city towards Cheltenham and Tewkesbury.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The next section (from Coombe Hill) was improved as one of the Tewkesbury roads, again from 1727.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Act refers to this as the Upper Way to Gloucester in contrast to the Lower Way, which went via Wainsload Bridge.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] When this Act was renewed in 1756, the road from Tewkesbury to a farmhouse called the Old Blue Ball (now Bluebell Farm) was also included.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This was in Earls Croome, Worcestershire, and was where one of the Worcester turnpikes ended.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Much of this stretch of the road originated as a Roman road, but the later road left the Roman line near Naunton in Ripple.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The name Stratford Bridge on the county boundary confirms its Roman origin there.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The A38 into Tewkesbury has been diverted away from the now declassified Gloucester Road along a new link road to the A438 east of the town centre.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The A38 resumes in Tewkesbury town centre where the A438 has always met the A38 near the Abbey.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The current A38 road follows from the southern end of one of the Worcester turnpike trust's roads which was originally set in 1726, by the Worcester Roads Act 1725 (12 Geo.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] 14), at Severn Stoke, but an act of Parliament of 1737, the Worcester Roads Act 1736 (10 Geo.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] 5), extended it to Upton Bridge (taking it past Bluebell Farm).
[src:gloucester/a38-road] North of the city, the road was a particularly important one as it connected the saltmaking centre of Droitwich with the River Severn.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] In 1706, this was described as heavily used for the 'carriage of salt, iron, coals and other wares'.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] When it was renewed by the Worcester to Droitwich Road Act 1725 (12 Geo.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] 20), it was extended from the Tything of Whistons to the Lower Slip of the Quay of Worcester; from Droitwich to Dyers Bridge (M5 junction 5) near Bromsgrove; and through the town of Droitwich from "Netherwith" [Netherwich] Bridge to a place called "Chapel on the Bridge".
[src:gloucester/a38-road] In 1749, this was again extended, by the Worcestershire Roads Act 1748 (22 Geo.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] 43), through the town of Bromsgrove to Spadebourne Bridge, immediately north of the town.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Where the road leaves Worcester, it again does not follow the line of the Roman road in the same direction until it picks up the Roman line, just south of Martin Hussingtree.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Roman road took a more direct line over Rainbow Hill and through Blackpole, now B4550.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] From Martin Hussingtree, the A38 closely follows the Roman line to beyond Bromsgrove.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The present road deviates from its line when it was originally classified at Droitwich where the main road is a bypass, the old road now mostly being B4090.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This happens again at Bromsgrove, where A38 is again a bypass, the old line mostly now being B4091 and Bromsgrove High Street (now partly pedestrianised, then through the town centre.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Bromsgrove Eastern Bypass was constructed in 1980.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] A short distance north of where the old A38 (now declassified) joins the Bromsgrove bypass, is Lickey End, where an old highway intersection has been replaced by junction 1 of M42 motorway.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Here, the road is joined from the southeast by the B4096, Alcester Road, which was from 1754 one of the roads of the Alcester turnpike trust.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The continuation northwards of B4096 is called Old Birmingham Road, because it was the original route of the turnpike to Birmingham, climbing to a pass in the Lickey Hills.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Roman road also went through the same pass, but its route to the pass was probably rather straighter.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Beyond the motorway junction, the A38 was turnpiked, not as the turnpike to Birmingham, but to Halesowen and Dudley, by the Bromsgrove and Birmingham Roads Act 1726 (13 Geo.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] 15) that also turnpiked Old Birmingham Road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Worcester and Warwick Roads Act 1741 (15 Geo.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] 7) appointed separate trustees for the Dudley Road in 1742 and the Bromsgrove to Birmingham Roads Act 1747 (21 Geo.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] 22) appointed trustees for the Birmingham Road in 1748.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The road continues from the M42 junction 1 towards Catshill and up a short incline at which there is a fork.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Prior to the construction of the M5 motorway in the early 1960s, the Halesowen Road continued West whilst Birmingham Road continued North to meet the existing dual carriageway just South of Rubery.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] After the M5 was constructed, all traffic was diverted along Halesowen Road (then the A459) which was widened and lit to provide a direct route for the A38 to meet the M5 at junction 4 at Lydiate Ash, with the dual carriageway continuing North to Rubery.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The original Birmingham Road survives to this day, but is noticeably lightly trafficked due to its cul-de-sac nature.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Its considerable width makes it a very popular route for learner drivers and as such is affectionately named by local people as "Learners Mile".
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The road from Lydiate Ash to Longbridge was laid out as a new road in the early 1960s to collaborate with the construction of the M5 motorway which opened in 1962.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The road passed through the centre of Rubery until the £770,000 (£13 million in 2025), Rubery Bypass opened in December 1965.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Lydiate Ash was the northern end of the M5 for many years in the 1960s, with traffic transferring onto the A38, which was diverted at this point to link with the M5.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] At Longbridge, new turnpike joined the Roman road and the original turnpike, and runs straight towards the city centre.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Northfield bypass, taking traffic away from the congested town centre opened on 11 April 2007.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Between Northfield and Selly Oak, the road is likely to have been in use in the medieval period as the road approximately follows the boundary of the former Weoley Park, the great park belonging to Weoley Castle.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This required new bridges to carry the Worcester and Birmingham Canal and the Cross-City railway line over the road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The destination of the Roman road was clearly Metchley Fort, but A38 turns away towards the city centre.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] After Selly Oak, the A38 takes the Bristol Road into the city as far as the Belgrave Interchange with the A4540 Middleway ring road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The city centre section takes a novel line, laid out as part of extensive reconstruction works in the 1960s, and is one of the few remaining pieces of the original "concrete collar" inner ring road.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The old road took a largely similar line as far as what is now Paradise Circus, before zig-zagging in a less direct and much slower route through the city centre, taking in the north side of New Street Station and then travelling along Corporation street to briefly rejoin its modern alignment.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This merges directly onto the M6 in both directions, as well as the A5127 and A38 surface streets, via an intertwined series of flyovers, meaning there is an uninterrupted run from the motorway and these suburban feeder roads all the way to the southern ring road junction.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Beyond Salford Circus, the A38 used to pass through Erdington, Wylde Green and particularly Sutton Coldfield town centres (and then Four Oaks, Mere Green and Shenstone) on its way towards Lichfield, before the extensive Sutton Coldfield Bypass was built.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This passes far to the east of its namesake town, as well as many other north Birmingham suburbs from Erdington through to Four Oaks, requiring an extensive diversion and use of redesignated link roads to access.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The bypass is two-lane dual carriageway throughout, offers a 40 mph (64 km/h) speed limit from Salford to Minworth, and is national speed limit (70 mph (110 km/h) for light vehicles) for most of the rest of its run.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] In Erdington and Sutton Coldfield, the original A5127 has been bypassed a second time by more minor urban relief roads, easing congestion in and allowing partial pedestrianisation of their respective town centre shopping areas.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Historically, it is not clear which turnpike trust was responsible for the section of road from Birmingham to Lichfield, or even whether it *was* a turnpike.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Also, the A5127 out of Sutton picks up the Roman road route a little north of Mere Green (having itself diverted via Metchley Fort, the modern suburbs of Perry Barr and Kingstanding, then Sutton Park and Four Oaks/Little Aston), and follows it to Lichfield.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The road (now A5127) from the county boundary at Shenstone Woodend, through Shenstone to Lichfield was one of the roads of the Lichfield Turnpike Trust, established in 1729.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] However, this section of the old A38 has been replaced by new dual carriageways.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Beyond Lichfield, the old A38 (now A5127) joins the Roman Ryknild Street at Streethay and immediately after that A5127 joins the present A38.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Ryknild Street had to that point run roughly parallel to A38, but following a different line from Metchley through Wall, its line sometimes being used by modern roads (including B4138).
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The section from Lichfield to Alrewas was dualled in 1958.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The £500,000 (£9.33 million in 2025), section from Alrewas to Wychnor Farm near Wychnor Hall, and the £150,000 (£2.8 million in 2025),section from Wychnor Farm to Barton Turn both opened in 1962.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This long stretch of road closely follows Ryknild Street (whose destination was the Roman fort at Little Chester) until just short of Branston where A38 swings west, perhaps to avoid low ground.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The Roman road is used by minor roads through the suburbs of Burton upon Trent and then A5121 to rejoin the present A38 beyond the river Dove near Clay Mills.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The road from Lichfield to Burton upon Trent was another of the roads maintained by the Lichfield Turnpike Trust from 1729.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This diverged from the present line at Branston, taking the road through the town centre, and is now classified as A5121.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The road from Burton to Derby was turnpiked in 1753.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Beyond the start of the Derby bypass, the old A38 has been reclassified as A5250.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] This follows Ryknild Street as far as Littleover.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] In March 1969, the 'Allestree Link Road', from the A6 at Allestree to the former A61 was opened, crossing the River Derwent and Midland Main Line.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Further improvements in the late 1960s and 1970s saw construction of the £5.2 million (£40.4 million in 2025) Mickleover bypass to the south-west of Derby opened on 19 February 1975.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] Although the government had approved the section through Allestree as early as 1974, before the Mickleover bypass had been completed, this section had many objections from nearby residents, delaying its construction (from the A52 to the A6).
[src:gloucester/a38-road] It was opposed directly by Derby Borough Council and the former Derby Higher Education College.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The £17 million (£57.8 million in 2025) road was eventually opened on 7 September 1983, known as *Queensway*.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] An extension of the A38 northwards, crossing the M1 at junction 28, and ending in Mansfield was built.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The £3 million (£17.6 million in 2025) Little Eaton-Holbrook Improvement opened on 3 October 1977.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The £12 million (£70.5 million in 2025) 10-mile (16 km) Ripley-Swanwick Bypass was opened by Eric Varley (MP for Chesterfield) on 21 October 1977, although the section from Alfreton to the Hartshay Hill roundabout with the A610 had been open to traffic since 5 September 1977.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] To the east of junction 28 of the M1, the road used to be the A615 until October 1977.
[src:gloucester/a38-road] The alignment of this road is relatively modern as the dangerous junction with Berristow Lane was improved to grade-separated in the late 1990s, incorporating access to a busy shopping centre.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The **A40** is a road which runs between London and Goodwick (Fishguard), in Wales.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] It is approximately 260 miles (420 km) long.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The eastern section from Denham, Buckinghamshire to Wheatley, Oxfordshire is better served by the M40 and its former function of linking London with Cheltenham and Gloucester has been taken by the M4, A419 and A417 via Swindon.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] In 1937, together with the A48 road, it formed parts of the London–Fishguard trunk road, as well as a part of the Newport–Shrewsbury trunk road.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Much of the A40's length within England has been superseded by motorways, such as the M40, and has lost its trunk road status, though it retains the status west of Gloucester and its entirety within Wales.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The road between Beaconsfield and Stokenchurch, that later became part of the A40, was put under the management of a turnpike trust by the **Beaconsfield and Stokenchurch Road Act 1718** (5 Geo.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The A40's 1923 route was from the City of London to Fishguard.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The road still begins and ends in the same places, but a number of changes have been made to its route.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] On 1 April 1937, parts of the road and the A48 road was classed to form the London–Fishguard trunk road.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Part of the road was also made part of the Newport–Shrewsbury trunk road.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The first change dates from 1935, between Ross-on-Wye and Abergavenny.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The original route of the A40 was via Skenfrith, avoiding Monmouth; this road was renumbered the B4521.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The A40 was rerouted via Raglan; between Ross and Raglan it replaced part of the A48, between Raglan and Llanvihangel-nigh-Usk it replaced the B4234, and between Llanvihangel and Abergavenny it replaced part of the A471.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Subsequently, the A40 was rerouted within west London.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Western Avenue dates from the 1930s, but was originally opened as the A403.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] After the Second World War, the A40 was rerouted along part of the A219 (west of Notting Hill) and Western Avenue.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The old route (via Acton, Ealing, Southall, Hayes, Hillingdon and Uxbridge) was renumbered the A4020.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Initially, the A40 went through the centre of Oxford, via Headington, Magdalen Bridge, the High Street, Carfax and Botley, and over the Swinford Toll Bridge to Eynsham.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] It was rerouted in the 1930s to follow the first section of the Oxford Ring Road to the north of the city, and then followed a direct line to bypass Eynsham.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The old route became part of the A420 to Botley, and the section between Botley and Eynsham was renumbered the A4141, renumbered again in the 1960s to the B4044.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] From the 1960s to 1990s a number of bypasses were built to divert the A40 around towns on the route, including Gloucester (1968), Monmouth (1964), Brecon (1980), Carmarthen (1984), St.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] In the mid-1980s a new dual carriageway was built for the A40 between Raglan and Abergavenny, and the 1935 route was renumbered the B4598.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] In central London it is High Holborn and then Oxford Street.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] At Marble Arch it joins the A5 Edgware Road as far as the Marylebone Flyover to become Westway then meets Western Avenue.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] For the greater part, this section is six lanes, otherwise four lanes.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] With two exceptions, Western Avenue forms a grade-separated motorway standard dual-carriageway between Paddington and the M40 motorway.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The two at-grade intersections are Gypsy Corner and Savoy Circus; both of which are traffic light controlled.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] At Denham Roundabout, the six lane Western Avenue flows into the M40.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The A40 branches off the Denham roundabout to run as a dual carriageway.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] After the junction with the A413, the A40 follows the same route as the M40 as a single carriageway, passing through Beaconsfield and High Wycombe.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Beyond Stokenchurch the road is much quieter; when meeting the B4009 and A329 those roads have priority.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Approaching Oxford, the A40 becomes a busy dual carriageway, carrying traffic from the M40 to Oxford and beyond.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The road forms the northern section of the Oxford Ring Road, crossing the A44 and the A34.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] In Oxford, it passes the Thornhill Park and Ride, where the OxfordTube, The Airline to Heathrow & Gatwick, & Oxford Park and Ride buses stop.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The A40 passes under the A34, reverting to single carriageway for 10 miles (16 km) until the dual carriageway just east of Witney with a grade-separated junction.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The dual carriageway finishes at a roundabout.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] For the rest of Oxfordshire and Gloucestershire until Cheltenham, other than for a few short stretches, the road is single carriageway.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] A height of 820 feet (250 m) above sea level is located 3 miles (4.8 km) west of the A429 junction.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Before Andoversford the A436 breaks off to the west to try to take traffic away from descending into the centre of Cheltenham itself.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The road travels through Cheltenham town centre along at least two parallel routes (neither is part of a one-way system: Sandford Road and Montpellier Terrace make up one part, Thirlestaine Road and Suffolk Road the other).
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Becoming a dual carriageway, it passes GCHQ in Cheltenham and the three-level stacked roundabout interchange with the M5 motorway.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] In February 2015, the Witney Oxford Transport Group proposed the reopening of Yarnton railway station as an alternative to improvements to the A40 road proposed by Oxfordshire County Council.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The A40 is the Gloucester bypass, most of which is dual carriageway.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The junction with the A48 to Chepstow is at Highnam.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] For the remainder of Gloucestershire, and a part of Herefordshire, the road is single carriageway until Ross-on-Wye.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] There it connects with the M50 motorway, and forms part of the high quality dual carriageway between South Wales and the English Midlands.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] From Ross-on-Wye to Monmouth the road follows the Wye Valley, an Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty, crossing the Wales–England border 1 mi (1.6 km) east of Monmouth.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Just west of Monmouth are twin tunnels; these are the only tunnels on the A40.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Near Raglan, the A40 has a grade separated junction with the A449.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The A40 continues as a dual carriageway to Abergavenny.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] At Abergavenny is the A40 junction with the Heads of the Valleys road, (A465) and the A4042.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Now the A465 becomes the primary route between the Midlands to the South Wales Valleys and Swansea; there is a dual-carriageway route to Carmarthen via the A465, M4 and A48.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The A40 becomes single carriageway and continues through Abergavenny, following the north side of the Usk valley through the eastern part of the Brecon Beacons National Park until Brecon.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] At Bwlch between Abergavenny and Brecon, the A40 is 660 feet (200 m) above sea level.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The A40 is dualed for over 1.5 miles (2.4 km) as it approaches a junction east of Brecon with the A470 north, which is the main north–south road through mid-Wales.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Continuing as a dual carriageway, the A40 and A470 concurrent bypass Brecon to the south, crossing the River Usk here.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] At the western end of the bypass is a further junction with the A470 south.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Beyond this point the A40 continues as a single carriageway, now south of the River Usk, and roughly follows the northern edge of the Brecon Beacons National Park.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] A height of 820 feet (250 m) above sea level is located less than 1 mile (1.6 km) east of Trecastle.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] In Llandovery the road crosses the Heart of Wales railway and the River Tywi; the road, railway and river then run parallel until Llandeilo, where the National Park ends and the railway turns south.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The A40 continues west along the Tywi valley to Carmarthen where as a dual carriageway it forms the eastern bypass, meeting the terminus of the A48 at Pensarn.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Here the A40 returns to being a primary route westwards.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] At Carmarthen the A40 crosses the River Tywi twice with two 90-degree junctions and continues on 10 miles (16 km) of dual carriageway as far as St.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Clears, where the dual carriageway ends at the junction with the A477 trunk road.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Now the A40 is a mixture of 2 or 3 lane single-carriageway to Haverfordwest and Fishguard.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] This section of road is controlled by the Welsh Government (formerly 'Welsh Assembly Government'), which describes it as "one of the lowest standard sections of the Trans European Road Network in the United Kingdom".
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The £60 million scheme was subject to a European Environmental Assessment.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Within a couple of years, the project appeared to be dying a very quiet death, causing local newspapers to report it being an election stunt for the two marginal constituencies that would best benefit from the improvements.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The following Welsh elections saw both constituencies change the party of majority.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The political party at the centre of the row instead directed the project deferment to damning environmental statements by Friends of the Earth Cymru.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The scheme was officially scrapped in 2008 after a Welsh Assembly committee decided to abandon the proposals.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Instead, it recommended upgrades to the existing route including bypasses around Robeston Wathen and Llanddewi Velfrey using a three-lane option.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] This was welcomed by the Friends of the Earth, saying "The dual carriageway on the A40 would increase traffic levels, increase the emission of greenhouse gases, it would be harmful for the environment, it would be hugely expensive.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] That money would be better spent on improving public transport, on health, on education, there's no need for it.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] We think the assembly committee has come to the right decision".
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The last improvement to the A40 on this section prior to the Welsh Assembly Government having the devolved responsibility for this road was a 4.1 kilometres (2.5 mi) £8 million bypass around Whitland.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Constructed in 1994, the road started east of Black Bridge on the original A40, then running north of the town before to a new roundabout just west of Llain Cottage.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The Secretary of State for Wales was asked a written question by Rhodri Morgan about adding a second carriageway to the Whitland bypass scheme, to which John Redwood replied "There are no proposals to add a second carriageway to the Whitland bypass.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] A new bypass has been granted approval by the Welsh Assembly Government at Llanddewi Velfrey in Pembrokeshire.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The scheme would improve the A40 between Llanddewi Velfrey and Penblewin, to the west of St Clears and meet the aim of the targeted investment in infrastructure along the east–west road corridor in south Wales.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] To the west of Ffynnon Wood, the road would then cross back over the original A40 to the east of Henllan Lodge in a way to maintain the tree lined avenue to Henllan, then run parallel to the A40 on the north side of the existing A40 to a new roundabout at Penblewin and the junction with the A478.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] This was originally known as the Blue and Purple routes during the Consultation in 2006 for which 75% preferred the blue route, and only 20% preferred the red route.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] 54% felt the section from Ffynnon Wood and Penblewin Roundabout needed improvement, with both orange and purple routes preferred by 42% of the respondents.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Welsh Water/Dwr Cymru expressed concerns with the red route affecting water mains and sewers, and Henllanfallteg Community Council felt the red route would not improve the quality of life in Llanddewi Velfrey.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Pembrokeshire County Council expressed concerns that the route planned was a single carriageway, and that within seven years, a dual carriageway would be required.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] A new bypass has been constructed between Penblewin and Slebech Park making the road straighter and with a '2+1' road layout to help improve overtaking opportunities.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Starting to the west of Toch Lane (approx.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] 2 kilometres (1.2 mi) east of Slebech), the route travels eastwards for 4.6 kilometres (2.9 mi), passing 200 metres (660 ft) south of Robeston Wathen, and ending 0.5 kilometres (0.31 mi) east of the village, just west of Flimstone Lane.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] Construction started on the route in February 2009, with the works completed and the new road opening 1 March 2011.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The scheme was nearly £14 million over the initial budget of £27.6 million, eventually costing £41.4 million.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The Welsh Assembly Government explains this increase as being the result of inflation and land costs, saying the original budget did not include either, as well as additional statutory procedures, additional works following some design standards, and the increase in VAT.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The Kell is located on a section of the A40 that forms a north–south corridor between Fishguard, 17 kilometres (11 mi) to the north and Haverfordwest, 7.5 kilometres (4.7 mi) to the south, close to Treffgarne and Spittal.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] This resulted in the road being rerouted through pasture to the east of the original road, taking a right hand bend about 160 metres (520 ft) south of The Old Mill, taking a 5.5% gradient, and rejoining the original road 210 metres (690 ft) north of The Kell.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The original road has subsequently been converted to an access road for The Old Mill, Beavers Lodge and The Kell, accessing the new road at The Old Mill.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The Fishguard Bypass was planned to provide a more direct route with greater capacity to the Port of Fishguard at Goodwick avoiding the town centre of Fishguard.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] It was constructed during the late 1990s and opened in 2000.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] It takes the form of a three-lane carriageway on an approx.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] 10% gradient around the western edge of Fishguard.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] It runs from its highest point at Rafael roundabout 1 km south of Fishguard town in a generally northerly direction to its lowest point at Windy Hall roundabout where it rejoins the old A40 route at Gasworks Hill.
[src:gloucester/a40-road] The bypass is concurrent with a section of the A487 trunk road with the A40 dominant.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester was founded as a Roman colony in AD 97, under Emperor Nerva as *Colonia Glevum Nervensis*.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It was granted its first charter in 1155 by Henry II.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 1216, Henry III, aged only nine years, was crowned with a gilded iron ring in the Chapter House of Gloucester Cathedral.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester's significance in the Middle Ages is underlined by the fact that it had a number of monastic establishments, including St Peter's Abbey, founded in 679 (later Gloucester Cathedral); the nearby St Oswald's Priory, founded in the 880s or 890s; and Llanthony Secunda Priory, founded in 1136.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The town is also the site of the siege of Gloucester in 1643, during which the city held out against Royalist forces in the First English Civil War.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A major attraction of the city is Gloucester Cathedral, which is the burial place of King Edward II and Walter de Lacy; it features in scenes from the *Harry Potter films*.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Other features of interest include the museum and school of art and science, the former county gaol (on the site of a Saxon and Norman castle), the Gloucester Shire Hall (now headquarters of the Gloucestershire County Council) and the Whitefield memorial church.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A park in the south of the city contains a spa, a chalybeate spring having been discovered in 1814.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Economically, the city is dominated by the service industries and has strong financial, research, distribution and light industrial sectors.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Historically, it was prominent in the aerospace industry.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 1926, the Gloucestershire Aircraft Company at Brockworth changed its name to the Gloster Aircraft Company because international customers claimed that the name *Gloucestershire* was too difficult to spell.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A sculpture in the city centre celebrates Gloucester's aviation history and its involvement in the jet engine.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] *Caerloyw* is a compound of *caer*, meaning 'fort, stronghold, castle', and *loyw*, a lenition of *gloyw* as it would have been pronounced by many speakers, meaning 'bright, shiny, glowy'.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A variant of the term *-cester/chester/caster* instead of the Welsh *caer* was eventually adopted.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The name Gloucester thus means roughly "bright fort".
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Mediaeval orthographies include *Caer Glow*, *Gleawecastre* and *Gleucestre*.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] This etymology was first suggested by the Austrian philologist, Alfred Holder, in 1896.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] An alternative etymology has been proposed, which argues that the first element of the place-name is related to a Welsh word signifying 'valiant', rendering 'Gloucester' to mean 'fortress of the valiant'.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Glevum was established around AD 48 at an important crossing of the River Severn and near to the Fosse Way, the early front line after the Roman invasion of Britain.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Initially, a Roman fort was established at present-day Kingsholm.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Twenty years later, a larger legionary fortress was built on slightly higher ground nearby, centred on present-day Gloucester Cross, and a civilian settlement grew around it.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Probably the Roman Legion XX Valeria Victrix was based here until 66 and then Legio II Augusta as they prepared to invade Roman Wales between 66 and 74 AD, who stayed later until around 87.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester became a *Colonia* in 97 as *Colonia Nervia Glevensium*, or *Glevum*, in the reign of Nerva.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It is likely that Glevum became the provincial capital of Britannia Prima.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Within about 15 years new privately constructed properties replaced the earlier barracks and public buildings, temples and bath houses were under construction in stone.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] On the site of the legionary *principia* an imposing central *forum* was laid out surrounded by colonnades and flanked on three sides by part-timbered ranges of shops.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Closing off the south of the forum was the 100m x 40m Basilica.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Many fine homes with mosaic floors were built in the town.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] At its height, Glevum may have had a population of as many as 10,000 people.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The entire area around Glevum was intensely Romanised in the second and third centuries with a higher than normal distribution of villas.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] At the end of the third century or the start of the fourth, major changes were made to the city's second-century wall.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It was replaced in two stages by a stronger and higher one of stone resting on massive reused stone blocks.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In the second stage, the blocks rested on deep timber foundation piles.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Stone external towers were added; two parallel wide ditches were also cut in front of the new walls.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Withdrawal of all Roman forces and many societal leaders in about the year 410 may have allowed leading families of the Dobunni tribe to regain power within the now Roman-influenced, interconnected and intermixed Celtic Brythonic local people.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] This intermix is reflected by the fact a large minority of basic words and available synonyms in Welsh have a Latin base.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In the *Anglo-Saxon Chronicle* Gloucester is shown as part of Wessex from the Battle of Deorham in 577.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] At some point afterwards, along with the rest of its shire excluding the Forest of Dean, Gloucester was part of the minor kingdom of the Hwicce.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 628, as a result of the Battle of Cirencester, that kingdom became a client or sub-kingdom of Mercia.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] From about 780, the Hwicce was no longer feigning any pretence as a kingdom and became part of Mercia.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Mercia, allied by matrimony and sharing a desire to counter the Danish onslaught as had conquered swathes of the wider island at large, submitted to Alfred the Great's Kingdom of Wessex in about 877–883.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A 20th-century writer intuitively adds that Roman stem Gleu- Glev- was, doubtless, pronounced without any final consonant.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] *Claudia Castra* is mentioned in the 18th century as a possible Latin name related to the city.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In the early 10th century, the remains of Saint Oswald were brought to a small church here and shrine built there, a draw for pilgrims.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The core street layout is thought to date to the reign of Æthelflæd in late Saxon times.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 1051, Edward the Confessor held court at Gloucester and was threatened there by an army led by Godwin, Earl of Wessex, but the incident resulted in a standoff rather than a battle.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] After the Norman Conquest, William Rufus made Robert Fitzhamon the first baron or overlord of Gloucester.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Fitzhamon had a military base at Cardiff Castle, and for the succeeding years the history of Gloucester was closely linked to that of Cardiff.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] During the Anarchy, Gloucester was a centre of support for the Empress Matilda, who was supported in her claim to the throne by her half-brother, Fitzhamon's grandson, Robert, 1st Earl of Gloucester (also known as Robert of Gloucester).
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] After this period of strife ended with the ascent of her son Henry to the throne Henry II of England, Henry granted Robert possession of Cardiff Castle, and it later passed to William Fitz Robert, 2nd Earl of Gloucester son of Robert.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The story of the Anarchy is vividly told in a series of 19th-century paintings by William Burges at the Castle.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Henry granted Gloucester its first charter in 1155, which gave the burgesses the same liberties as the citizens of London and Winchester.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A second charter of Henry II gave them freedom of passage on the River Severn.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The first charter was confirmed in 1194 by King Richard I.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The privileges of the borough were greatly extended by the charter of King John (1200), which gave freedom from toll throughout the kingdom and from pleading outside the borough.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 1216, King Henry III, aged only 9 years, was crowned with a gilded iron ring in the Chapter House of Gloucester Cathedral.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] During his reign, Eleanor, Fair Maid of Brittany his cousin was briefly imprisoned at Gloucester Castle as state prisoner from 1222 to 1223, and from 1237 to 1238, in addition to sometime during the reign of King John.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It also has some very early churches including St Mary de Lode Church, Gloucester near the Cathedral and the Norman St Mary de Crypt Church, Gloucester in Southgate Street.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Additionally, there is evidence of a Jewish community in Gloucester as early as 1158–1159; they lived around present-day East Gate Street and had a synagogue on the south side, near St Michael's church.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester was probably the home of Rabbi Moses, who established an important Anglo-Jewish family.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Jews of the town were falsely accused by the Dominican monks of murdering a child, Harold of Gloucester, in an attempt to establish a cult similar to that of William of Norwich, which failed entirely.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Nevertheless, the accusations were recycled around the time of the Edict of Expulsion.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In January 1275, Eleanor of Provence expelled Jews from all of the towns within her dower lands, and the Jews of Gloucester were ordered to move to Bristol but finding an especially difficult situation there, relocated to Hereford.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In the Middle Ages, the main export was wool, which came from the Cotswolds and was processed in Gloucester; other exports included leather and iron (tools and weapons).
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester also had a large fishing industry at that time.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 1222, a massive fire destroyed part of Gloucester.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] One of the most significant periods in Gloucester's history began in 1378 when Richard II convened Parliament in the city.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Parliaments were held there until 1406 under Henry IV of England.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Parliament Rooms at the Cathedral remain as testimony to this important time.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester was incorporated by King Richard III in 1483, the town being made a county in itself.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The city's charter was confirmed in 1489 and 1510, and other charters of incorporation were received by Gloucester from Queen Elizabeth I and King James I.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Princess Mary visited Gloucester in September 1525 accompanied by her ladies and gentlewomen.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] She was met by the Mayor, John Rawlins, at Quedgeley.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Her father Henry VIII and his then Queen, Anne Boleyn, visited in July 1535.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] They used Gloucester as a base for hunting trips to Painswick, Coberley, and Miserden.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] They left Gloucester for Leonard Stanley, on their way to Berkeley Castle.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester was the site of the execution by burning of John Hooper, Bishop of Gloucester, in the time of Queen Mary in 1555.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 1580, Gloucester was awarded the status of a port by Queen Elizabeth I.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The 16th and 17th centuries saw the foundation of two of Gloucester's grammar schools: the Crypt School in 1539 and Sir Thomas Rich's School in 1666.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Both still flourish as grammar schools today, along with Ribston Hall and Denmark Road High School.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] During the English Civil War, the fall of nearby Bristol encouraged the reinforcement of the existing town defences.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The siege of Gloucester commenced in 1643 in which the besieged parliamentarians emerged victorious.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Royalist's plan of bombardment and tunnelling to the east gate failed due to the inadequacy of the Royalist artillery and the besieged sniping and conducting artillery fire on the Royalist encampment.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] By the mid-17th century, only the gatehouse and keep of Gloucester Castle remained, the latter of which was being used as a gaol until it was deemed unsuitable and demolished in the late 1780s.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] By 1791, the new gaol was completed leaving no trace of the former castle.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In the 19th century, the city grew with new buildings including Wellington Parade and the Grade II listed Picton House (c.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The 1896 Gloucester smallpox epidemic affected some 2000 residents.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] During the Second World War, two petroleum storage depots were constructed in Gloucester.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A Government Civil Storage depot with six 4,000-ton semi-buried tanks was constructed on the Berkeley Canal in 1941/42 by Shell-Mex and BP and connected to the pipeline that ran from the Mersey to the Avon.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It was also connected to the Air Force Reserve Depot and a Shell Mex and BP facility for road and rail loading.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Due to severe tank corrosion, it was demolished in 1971/2 and disposed of in 1976.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The second depot was an Air Force Reserve Depot with four 4,000-ton semi-buried tanks constructed in 1941/42 by Shell, Shell-Mex and BP at the Monk Meadow Dock on the Canal.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Originally, delivery was by road, rail and barge and pipeline.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It was also connected to the docks and to the Shell Mex and BP installation for rail and road loading facilities and the civil storage site.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It was transferred from the Air Ministry to the Ministry of Power in 1959, closed in the 1990s and disposed of in the later 2000s.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester's most important citizens include Robert Raikes (founder of the Sunday School movement) who is still commemorated by the name of Robert Raikes' House in Southgate Street.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Its most infamous citizen was Fred West.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In July 2007, Gloucester was hit badly by a flood that struck Gloucestershire and its surrounding areas.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Hundreds of homes were flooded, but the event was most memorable because of its wider impact – about 40,000 people were without power for 24 hours, and the entire city (plus surrounding areas) was without piped water for 17 days.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 2009, Gloucester Day was revived as an annual day of celebration of Gloucester's history and culture.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The day originally dates from the lifting of the Siege of Gloucester in 1643, during which the city held out against Royalist forces during the First English Civil War.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester is one of the few cities in England with two coats of arms.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The first consists of three chevrons surrounded by ten roundels.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The chevrons come from the arms of the Clare family, who were earls of Gloucester from the 12th to the 14th centuries, while the roundels come from the arms of the Bishop of Worcester, whose bishopric historically encompassed Gloucester.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] This coat is the older of the two, though it is usually termed the "Commonwealth coat", as it was not officially granted to the city until 1652, during the Commonwealth period.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The crest and supporters (lions bearing broadswords and trowels) were also adopted at this time, along with the motto *Fides Invicta Triumphat* ("unconquered faith triumphs", in reference to the royalist siege withstood by the city in 1643).
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The second coat, termed the "Tudor coat", was granted in 1538.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It features the roses of York and Lancaster, the boar's head of Richard III, a ceremonial sword and cap, and two horseshoes surrounded by nails, to represent Gloucester's historical association with ironworking.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Although grants made by Commonwealth heralds were nullified after the Restoration, the Commonwealth coat continued to be used by the city rather than the Tudor coat.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Commonwealth coat, along with the crest and supporters, was legally granted to the city by letters patent dated 16 April 1945.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] This was reconfirmed in 1974 following the local government changes of that year.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] There are two tiers of local government covering Gloucester, at district (city) and county level: Gloucester City Council and Gloucestershire County Council.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Quedgeley area of the city is a civil parish with a town council, forming a third tier of local government; the remainder of the city is an unparished area.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester was an ancient borough, being treated as a borough from Saxon times and being granted its first known borough charter by Henry II in 1155.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 1483 the town of Gloucester was given the right to appoint its own magistrates, making it a county corporate, administratively independent from the surrounding county of Gloucestershire.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] When the Diocese of Gloucester was founded in 1541, the town was given the right to call itself a city.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The city was reformed to become a municipal borough in 1836 under the Municipal Corporations Act 1835.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] When elected county councils were established in 1889, Gloucester was considered large enough to provide its own county-level services, and so it was made a county borough, independent from Gloucestershire County Council.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester Guildhall at 23 Eastgate Street was built in 1892 and served as the city's administrative headquarters until 1986, when the council moved to North Warehouse at Gloucester Docks.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] On 1 April 1974, the modern district of Gloucester was formed under the Local Government Act 1972, covering the same area as the abolished County Borough of Gloucester.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The reforms also saw the city become subordinate to Gloucestershire County Council, losing the independence it had held since 1483.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The parish of Quedgeley was subsequently transferred into Gloucester from Stroud District in 1991.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Quedgeley retains its own parish council, unlike the rest of Gloucester, which is an unparished area.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 2017, Quedgeley Parish Council changed its name to Quedgeley Town Council, making it a town within a city.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester is the county town of Gloucestershire, and is the 53rd largest settlement in the United Kingdom by population.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It has the traditional lowest bridging point of the longest river in Great Britain, connecting it with Over.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The 2011 census recorded that the city had a population of 121,921 and by 2016 its population was estimated to be 128,488.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The city's urban area extends beyond its boundaries, with several outlying districts.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The 2021 census gave the population of the Gloucester Urban Area as 169,061, absorbing areas such as Brockworth and Churchdown.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The city is located on the eastern bank of the River Severn, sheltered by the Cotswolds to the east, while the Forest of Dean and the Malvern Hills rise to the west and north, respectively.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester is an inland port, linked via the Gloucester and Sharpness Canal which runs from Gloucester's docks to the Severn Estuary, allowing larger ships to reach the docks than would be possible on the tidal reaches of the river itself, which go well north of the city to Haw Bridge.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The wharfs, warehouses and the docks themselves fell into disrepair until their renovation in the 1980s.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Some warehouses now house the Gloucester Waterways Museum, others were converted into residential flats, shops and bars.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Additionally, the Soldiers of Gloucestershire Museum is located in the Custom House.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester is made up of a variety of neighbourhoods, some of which correspond to electoral divisions of the City Council.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] † Quedgeley is the only town within the city's borders.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Because of this it has its own town council.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In May 2024, under plans by Gloucestershire County Council, it was reported that there are secret talks to formally merge the conurbations of Cheltenham and Gloucester with each other.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The plans suggest that around ten new garden towns could be built around the green belt at Boddington which if removed would result in the complete merger of both boroughs.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Doing so would facilitate and effectively merge the two into a supercity.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The move has been criticised by both Cheltenham Borough Council and Gloucester City Council.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester Cathedral, in the north of the city near the river, originates in the foundation of an abbey dedicated to Saint Peter in 681.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It is the burial place of King Edward II and Walter de Lacy.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The cathedral (mainly its cloisters) was used for corridor scenes in the films *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone*, *Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets* and *Harry Potter and the Half Blood Prince*.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The crypt was used for a scene in *Sherlock* Christmas special.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Attached to the deanery is the Norman prior's chapel.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In St Mary's Square outside the Abbey gate, the Bishop of Gloucester, Bishop John Hooper, was martyred under Queen Mary I in 1555.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A good number of medieval and Tudor period gabled and half timbered houses survive from earlier periods of Gloucester's history.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Old Judges House, at 26 Westgate Street, is the largest surviving medieval timber-framed building in England and has undergone a major restoration by English Heritage.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] At the point where the four principal streets intersected stood the Tolsey (town hall), which was replaced by a modern building in 1894.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] None of the old public buildings are left except for the New Inn in Northgate Street.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It is a timbered house, with strong, massive external galleries and courtyards.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It was built around 1450 by John Twyning, a monk.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Kings Square is at the heart of the city centre and occupies what was once a cattle market and bus station.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Officially opened in 1972, it was the centrepiece of a radical redesign of the city, The Jellicoe Plan, which was first proposed in 1961.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It stands beside the Debenham's (formerly Bon Marché) store built in the early 1960s.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Many of the features of the redevelopment have since been dismantled; the brutalist concrete fountains in the middle of the square have gone and the overhead roadways which linked three multi storey car parks around the centre have been either closed or dismantled.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The main bus station received a Civic Trust Award in 1963 but has since been demolished, with a new bus station being constructed on the same site during 2018.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 2012 a £60 million plan was unveiled to revamp the square.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 2014, the prominent Golden Egg restaurant was demolished and a new look public space was created.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A prior archaeological dig revealed a Roman house underneath.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] An indoor market opened in Eastgate Street in 1968, followed by the Eastgate Shopping Centre in 1973.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Kings Walk Shopping Centre was built between 1969 and 1972.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The corner of Eastgate Street and Brunswick Road was redeveloped around this time; Roman remains unearthed below street level in 1974 may be seen through a glass observation panel outside the Boots building, which opened in 1980.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The HSBC building on the Cross was renovated and a modern extension added to the Westgate Street aspect in 1972 which received a Civic Trust Award.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Sainsbury's opened a supermarket in Northgate Street in 1970; it retains its original interior.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Opposite, Tesco opened a large two-storey supermarket in June 1976 on the site of a demolished chapel.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] This is now occupied by Wilkinson's after Tesco moved to Quedgeley in 1984.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Asda opened its first store in Gloucester in Bruton Way in 1983.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester Leisure Centre opened on the corner of Eastgate Street and Bruton Way in September 1974 and was redeveloped and rebranded (as "GL1") in August 2002.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester Central railway station was rebuilt in 1977 to serve both the original traffic to that railway station and the services from the closed Gloucester Eastgate railway station (former Midland Railway) which had stood on another site further east along the same road.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Opposite the station stands one of the city's largest office blocks, Twyver House, opened in 1968, which houses the regional Land Registry.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The main shopping streets were pedestrianised in the late 1980s.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The 1966 *Heights Plan for Gloucester* sought to restrict construction of tall buildings and defend spiritual values by protecting views of Gloucester Cathedral.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The tower of Gloucestershire Royal Hospital, started in 1970 and completed in August 1975, can be seen from miles around.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In Brunswick Road, a brown concrete tower, which housed classrooms at the Gloucestershire College of Arts and Technology (now moved to a site near Llanthony Bridge).
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The tower was added incongruously to the existing 1930s Technical College buildings in 1971 which has now been demolished.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Clapham Court, a tall block of flats, stands in Columbia Close, between London Road and Kingsholm Road.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It was built in 1963 and stands on what was once Columbia Street in a small district formerly known as Clapham.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Other features of interest include the museum and school of art and science, the former county jail (on the site of a Saxon and Norman castle), the Shire Hall (now headquarters of the County Council) and the Whitefield memorial church.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] West of this, across the canal, are the remains (a gateway and some walls) of Llanthony Secunda Priory, a cell of the mother abbey in the Vale of Ewyas, Monmouthshire, which in the reign of King Edward IV became the secondary establishment.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The city's Northgate and Southgate streets feature a series of public art mosaic panels depicting Gloucester's medieval trades made by artists Gary Drostle and Rob Turner in 1998 and 1999.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Eastgate and Westgate streets feature a series of mosaic panels made by arts group 'The Pioneers'.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Three Choirs Festival, originating in the 18th century and one of the oldest music festivals in the British Isles, is held in Gloucester every third year, the other venues being Hereford and Worcester.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester hosted the festival in 2019, and it is next due in the city in 2023.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The city's main theatre and cultural venue is the Guildhall.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Guildhall hosts a huge amount of entertainment, including live music, dance sessions, a cinema, bar, café, art gallery and much more.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Leisure Centre, GL1, hosts concerts and has a larger capacity than the Guildhall.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The annual Gloucester International Rhythm and Blues Festival takes place at the end of July and early August.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester International Cajun and Zydeco Festival, the largest in the UK and longest-running in Europe, runs for a weekend in January each year.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A Medieval Fayre is held in Westgate Street each year during the summer.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester is also noted as the home of the Frightmare Halloween Festival, the largest Halloween festival in the South West.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The main museum in the city is The Museum of Gloucester but there are several other important museums.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Tailor of Gloucester House which is dedicated to the author Beatrix Potter can be found near the cathedral.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Since 2013 Gloucester has marked Armed Forces Day with a Drum Head Service held on College Green in the shadow of the cathedral.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] This is followed by a parade of serving forces, veterans and cadets through the city centre to the docks for a family day with military and military-related charity displays and entertainment in Back Badge Square in front of the Soldiers of Gloucestershire Museum.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Nature in Art is a gallery dedicated to the display of works of art inspired by the natural world.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The city features in the popular, well-known nursery rhyme (of unknown date and origin) about a Doctor Foster, who reportedly visited the city, got wet, and swore to stay away as a result.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester has many churches, and historically has also had many dissenting chapels.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It may have been the old proverb "as sure as God's in Gloucester" that provoked Oliver Cromwell to declare that the city had "more churches than godliness".
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester was the host of the first Sunday school in England; this was founded by Robert Raikes in 1780.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In the neighbourhood around St Mary de Crypt there are slight remains of Greyfriars and Blackfriars monasteries, and also of the city wall.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Under the Golden Fleece (The Monks Bar) and Saracen's Head inns early vaulted cellars still remains.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In addition, in the city is St Peter's Roman Catholic Church, a Grade II* listed building.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] During the construction of the Boots store on the corner of Brunswick Road and Eastgate Street in 1974, Roman remains were found.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] These can be seen through a glass case on the street.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] At the back of the Gloucester Furniture Exhibition Centre part of the city's South Gate can be seen.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Comprehensives include Henley Bank High School, Beaufort Co-operative Academy, St Peter's High School (Catholic school), Chosen Hill School, Severn Vale School, Gloucester Academy, Barnwood Park School and Churchdown School Academy.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] There is a Steiner Waldorf School founded in 1937 with a High School added just after the Second World War.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The city is home to one of three campuses of the University of Gloucestershire, based at Oxstalls, just outside the city centre.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The university has also purchased the former Debenhams store in the city centre with a new campus due to open there in 2023.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The university also manages student accommodation and halls of residence in the city, with the other campuses based in Cheltenham 7 miles away.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The M5 motorway, opened in 1971, runs east of the city boundary.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Junction 12 serves south Gloucester and Quedgeley; junction 11a serves central Gloucester; and junction 11 serves north Gloucester.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The A38 runs north–south through Gloucester, connecting the city with Tewkesbury and Bristol.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The A40 runs west to east, connecting Gloucester with Cheltenham to the east (via a dual carriageway section known as *The Golden Valley Bypass*) and the Forest of Dean and South Wales to the West.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The A46 and A4173 links Stroud, and the A417 links Cirencester in the south-east and Ledbury in the north-west.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester has a network of cycle paths.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Until the construction of the Severn Bridge in 1966, Gloucester was the lowest road bridging point on the river and hence was an important settlement between South Wales and the southernmost counties of England including London.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Severn has a small anabranch here to reach Alney Island and then the main western bank.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A bridge at Over, built by Thomas Telford in 1829, still stands, notable for its very flat arch, but its fragility and narrowness means it is disused; since 1974, it has been paralleled by a modern bridge.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The Gloucester to Newport Line railway bridge is close to both, the lowest crossing of the UK's longest river until the Severn Railway Bridge 1879–1960, which was coupled with the Severn Tunnel in 1886, the present holder of that status.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester was the site of the Gloucester Railway Carriage and Wagon Company railway works, which have now closed.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A new station at Hunts Grove has been considered on the southern edge of the city near Quedgeley, as part of *MetroWest* plans to extend Bristol commuter services to the city.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Most local buses are run by Stagecoach West, centred at a depot on London Road, with connections to Cheltenham, Stroud, Ross-on-Wye and other smaller communities.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] For many years, there were both stopping and express services to Worcester and Birmingham operated by Midland Red and later Midland Red West, but this connection was lost due to service reductions.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] National Express Coaches operate the 444 route to London.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester is linked to the Severn Estuary by the Gloucester and Sharpness Canal, which is navigable by small coasters.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The city is linked to the River Avon and Stourport-on-Severn by the navigable part of the River Severn, which is navigable by river craft of a few hundred tonnes' displacement.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester Docks mark the Normal Tidal Limit (NTL) of the river.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester was formerly linked to Ledbury and Hereford by the Herefordshire and Gloucestershire Canal; and subsequently by the Ledbury and Gloucester Railway, which used the southern section of the former canal, until it also closed in 1964.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] This canal is now being restored and the restored canal basin in the adjacent village of Over is a local attraction.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Commercial airports with scheduled services are Bristol, Birmingham and Cardiff 40–60 miles away; global hub Heathrow is about 100 miles by road and shares with Gloucester its main rail interchange at London Paddington.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucestershire Airport, sited 8 miles east of the city, is a private and special charters airfield.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester has a long history in the aerospace business.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] In 1926 the Gloucestershire Aircraft Company at Brockworth changed its name to the Gloster Aircraft Company because international customers claimed that the name "Gloucestershire" was too difficult to spell.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Frank Whittle's pioneering turbojet engine powered the Gloster E.28/39, the first British jet aircraft, which first flew at the company's airfield at Brockworth.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] This is commemorated by the pub "The Whittle" at Gloucester Business Park, which now occupies the site.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Roads in the business park are named after other Gloster aircraft and a small statue overlooks the site of the old main runway.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Messier-Dowty's landing gear plant and GE Aviation Dowty Propellers plants are on the outskirts of the city.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] The large insurer Ecclesiastical Insurance is based in the city, as is its owner, the charity Benefact Trust.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Lloyds Banking Group and TSB Bank each have an office in Barnwood, the former previously having been the headquarters of Cheltenham & Gloucester Building Society.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester was the home of Priday, Metford and Company Limited, a family milling firm which survived for over one hundred years, and hydraulic engineering firm Fielding & Platt.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester Business Park is a business park on the outskirts on the city and is home to a number of big brands including Fortis and BAE Systems Applied Intelligence.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Unilever Gloucester has made ice cream, such as the Cornetto (frozen dessert) and Viennetta, since 1962, in Barnwood.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] It has been the largest ice-cream factory in Europe.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] BBC Radio Gloucestershire has its studios on London Road in Gloucester.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Heart West, previously Severn Sound, is based in Bristol.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester FM is a community radio station specialising in black and urban music.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Local radio is broadcast from transmitters on Churchdown Hill (Chosen Hill).
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] For regional television in Gloucester is covered by BBC West Midlands & BBC West on BBC One and ITV Central & ITV West Country on ITV.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Television signals are received from either Ridge Hill or Mendip TV transmitters.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] A number of TV and film productions have been filmed in Gloucester; most notably at the cathedral and docks.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] These include three of the Harry Potter films, *Doctor Who*, *Outlaw* and *Alice in Wonderland: Through the Looking Glass*.
[src:gloucester/gloucester-p01] Gloucester was also twinned with Gouda in the Netherlands, but this twinning ended in 2015.
